The government wants to reduce the torture of "witches", a brochure has been published.
In Burkina Faso, women who are declared witches have common traits.
They are part of the older generation, cannot work for health reasons, are single and have no children.
The one who becomes a "witch" is isolated so as not to threaten the rest of the village.
"Man has very rarely this destiny".
"Young women in good health are not judged either because they are working and giving birth", says a sister who works in the capital of the West African country of Burkina Faso, in a special institution for more than 100 women who have been rejected by society.
The local government decided to intervene against this unusual "social measure".
He's published a pamphlet that should help curb the witch hunts.
There's a hiccup in the case.
"More than 70 percent of the adults in Burkina Faso cannot read", warned the newspaper Die Standard of the drawbacks of written instruction.
Accusations of witchcraft are common in other African countries.
In Ghana, neighboring Burkina Faso, Ammy Hemma, a 72-year-old woman, died after being tortured by three women and a man and then burned with oil they sprayed on her.
The BBC server transmitted this information.
The criminals claim it was the evil eye.
According to their version, the oil used for ritual anointing caught fire when the woman touched it.
The oil was ignited, it was said, when the team tried to "banish the evil spirit" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is approved by people of all educational levels.
The daily Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso as saying: "The soul-eaters have always been a danger".
While Burkina Faso is working to reduce the witch hunts, Gambia has seen the President himself involved in them as recently as last year.
"Gambian President Dzammi, after the death of his aunt, launched a large witch hunt which, it seems, may have participated in his death and tried by black magic to kill the President as well".
"Shamans from nearby Guinea came to the rescue and brought to the presidential farm in Kanilai, under the protection of police officers and the President's personal guard, men and women chosen at random from Gambian villages", Amnesty International said in a message.
At the farm, the prisoners were made to drink a herbal potion with hallucinogenic effects, which caused other effects on the kidneys and intestines.
Two prisoners did not survive.
International pressure led to the release of about a thousand people.
The tenant of Bakal: The heat is on, he signed a higher rent.
A large elderly man walked out the door of the customer centre of the RPG Byty company of the "coal baron" Zdenek Bakal, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
He was carrying a file with three new leases for three apartments: his own, his daughter's and his son's, who is currently serving a sentence.
The deregulation has increased the rent for these three people.
Instead of paying 3500 the son will have to pay 4100 crowns for a 2+1 apartment of the second category from next year.
"And there's no hot water and the heating runs on solid fuel", points to the new contract from his son the man who has the signing power.
"But I signed anyway", he said, angry and half resigned.
The citizens' association of apartments BytyOKD.cz which described the new rental conditions as "immoral and indecent", advises tenants not to sign and wait until December 7, when a notice will be published explaining the method to follow to claim.
But the man responds to this by a hand gesture.
"One says this, the other says that", he frowns.
The Ostrava region is becoming the laboratory of deregulation.
After the New Year, this is what awaits most apartments in the Czech Republic whose rents do not correspond to the market price.
Aktualne.cz therefore decided to personally visit the "laboratory".
The RPG waiting room on Havirovska Street is one of four in the Ostrava region and it is already full on Tuesday at 09:00 am.
Right next to the door is a security guard from a security company with a device to call customers.
A special "Hire 2011" button is on the touch screen.
One tap and a piece of paper with a number on it comes out of the machine.
You don't have time to read your number "157" as your number already starts to light up on the big screen under the top of the waiting room.
In a split second, it's your turn.
After a short while, an old couple arrive to inquire about the rent, but the new rent doesn't seem to apply to the people in the waiting room.
Most people came to deal with the usual problems of the day - claims for repairs, insurance incidents and so on.
In the Ostrava region, people in more than 44000 apartments in the RPG portfolio have been receiving mail with the new lease contracts in their mailboxes since about mid-November.
RPG Byty offers them rent increases from 15 to 38 percent.
The special ticket office for new rentals has been open to the public since 18 November.
"It's been working for almost a week, so it's still a trial", the cashier answers after a moment of hesitation, when the customer introduces himself as a journalist.
The de-mining and former miners' apartments in Bakal are a very sensitive local issue.
The Social Democrats' deputy speaker of parliament Lubomir Zaoralek from the Ostrava region made a rather strong statement before the elections and it is now filling the local newspapers.
"20 years after them, I want a new floor".
"They didn't even change a fucking board in the bathroom", the man said.
However, according to the employees, it is mainly pensioners who come to make sure that they will receive a refund on the new rent if they sign now as promised by RPG in a special offer.
It's a half-rent rebate for other tenants who sign their new lease before December 15th.
But the "deregulation" counter on Havirovaska Street is not really overwhelmed by questions.
"Of the 360 customers who came yesterday, only 40 to 50 came to rent", says the clerk at the counter.
Yet RPG is still offering individual rent interviews on its website and in its storefronts when needed.
If the two parties cannot agree on the rent, an independent tribunal will decide.
'This is not about threats but only about informing about the unique and legitimate way to act legally,' RPG says on its website.
"No one here will go to court" thought one of the employees of RPG Byty and the man in the street in front of the customer center agreed with her.
"I have 13,000 crowns in pension and I have 5,000 crowns left to eat, I don't have enough to go to court", he says.
The employee suddenly feels uncomfortable.
"We will see".
"Mr Zaoralek in the media asked that no one sign and so people wait", she said.
The rent regulation ends in the Czech Republic with the beginning of 2011 and the increases, according to RPG Byty, are an economic necessity.
"And, moreover, the current rents still do not reach the level necessary for the simple maintenance of the housing fund", recalls Pavel Klimes, director of the residential portfolio of the company RPG Byty, that it is precisely the neglect of the housing fund that makes the tenant angry is the main reason for the increase in rent.
However, in the five years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest 4 billion in apartments with the rent, in the four years from 2011 to 2014 it should be 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling in front of the upholstered chairs in the waiting room on Havirosvka Street, however, repeats some information shown in red.
'The rent increase in 2011 is 15 percent and concerns no less than 31200 apartments, i.e. more than 90 percent of the RPG apartments.'
"And it will always be at most 7.50 CZK per m2 per month", the screen says.
The 38 percent increase is for only 400 apartments in the RPG portfolio.
"In these cases, it is an increase of a very low amount of 19.66 CZK per m2", adds RPG.
Next year, the rent will be the same for 2,600 apartments.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not cause a radical increase but a gradual one over 4 to 8 years.
It adds other commitments: all the money from the rent increases (see graph) is returned to the apartments in the form of savings on heating - new windows and heating.
Those who sign the agreement on the rent increase have priority.
The nursery school is also part of the offices of the architects.
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of the Arch. Design company.
No one would have expected it to also house a mini-kindergarten with everything needed - colorful walls, imaginative furniture, toys and finally a miniature playground on the terrace.
Since October last year, children of Arch. design employees can go there.
The architectural design firm Arch Design, whose workshops have produced a large number of buildings in Brno, has been designing its mini-enterprise nursery school since the first drafts of the Avriopoint building.
It employs about 90 people, mostly of childbearing age and it was important to her that the women architects and project managers could quickly return to work.
Along with parttime employment contracts, kindergarten is a bonus offered to employees by Arch Design as part of its social programme.
This gives builders and architects the opportunity to combine demanding work with care for children.
The idea for this nursery school was conceived by Arch.Design employees themselves and with the support of the management they were able to obtain a grant from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The mini-nursery is financed by the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme for Human Resources and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
With the financial allocations (CZK 2.8 million) they were able to buy equipment and apparatus and after two years to provide qualified staff and start-up.
After the use of the financing allowance (two years) the company Arch. Design. has the obligation after 3 years to run the mini-nursery school on its own funds.
The project took a year to prepare and it was the Economy rating company that helped to apply for funding.
The children are cared for by qualified staff, with a nurse and a kindergarten teacher on duty all day. Children can attend kindergarten without age limit, but most are over three years old.
As it is a "mini-kindergarten" there can be only 5 children present at the same time, but during the day there are more who change.
The school is flexible in its functioning according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use the school regardless of the hierarchical position.
Although the programme is individual care and education, the mini-kindergarten is similar to the pre-school programme.
The children do not just play but also receive quality education - from the beginning to the preparation for school benches English is taught.
The classroom is equipped not only with imaginative toys and games but also with a computer that the children can use.
The presence of young children in society creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can monitor their child at any time and not have the stress of being late to pick up the children at a school far from the parents' place of work.
So parents are using their work time in the most productive way.
It is no wonder that a natural relationship of loyalty develops between the employee and the employer.
Arch.Design.is thus listed among the companies that offer a preferential bonus for the recruitment of new employees and which are family-friendly and through this programme strengthens the marketing of HR.
The house of bones still fascinates after 100 years.
The roof resembles the back of a prehistoric saurian, the staircase a dinosaur spine, and the balconies open fish mouths.
This is the case of the Casa Battlo in Barcelona, designed by architect Antoni Gaudi.
Because of its organic forms, the house was given the nickname "Bone House" by the locals.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade resembling scales and curves everywhere - these are all the epic features of Antoni Gaudí's Art Nouveau.
The front facade of the house has its dreamlike lines, its pleasant colors and textures that recall nature and animals.
A closer look reveals the precise geometry, rhythm and order of the work.
At night the facade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit up in such a way that the impression of brilliance of the colors is enhanced.
The winding and twisting of shapes also appears in the interiors with the same measure.
The wood is used in the form of waves for window frames, balustrades, door decorations, and for the eyes and slats.
The Battlo house which stands in the Eixample district in the Passeig de Gracia shopping street at number 43, was born from the construction of a house in 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a wealthy entrepreneur, initially insisted on demolishing the old building and building a brand new one but quickly accepted Gaudi's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a house with multiple dwellings was not thought of by Gaudi alone.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It was on his project that the decorations for an apartment representing the owner of the building and the use of the mosaic for the facade were born.
For the façade also worked other artists and designers.
The joint work on the plans for the Casa Battlo house began with a successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudi's house Casa Mila and the Guell Park in which there are other works by Gaudi.
The locals nicknamed the hot house right after it was finished because of its organic shapes "the Bone House".
Others, because of the specific mechanism of opening the windows, have called it "the house that squeaks".
They say that on top of the building there is a sword similar to that of Saint George the patron of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of the building contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudi designed a unique central heating system for the house, with ventilation vents and typical chimneys.
Their 45-degree inclination seems odd.
During the creation Gaudi absolutely did not respect the building directives of that time and did not let himself be hindered by them.
At the beginning of the construction he obtained from the city the building permit, knowing, of course, that the data on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years later during the finishing the city council was horrified and asked for modifications.
For example, the members of the city council were not pleased that the pillars of the building were encroaching on the public sidewalk.
There was never any change, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the city's appeal, Josep Battlo asked (and got satisfaction) for permission to rent the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor was a common living room and on the third a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-story house is divided by a staircase that leads up to an independent roof terrace.
All the right angles and straight lines were cancelled by the basic elements of the reconstruction and replaced by curved walls.
Gaudí also worked on the modern concept of linking spaces.
The common area can be completely connected by opening the doors of the lounges and the upper class can communicate comfortably or else limit the private space for more intimate conversations.
The house with Gaudi's reconstruction received in addition to new facades a non-traditional roof and two additional floors.
Gaudi's play with light is also impressive, with the blue and white glass tiles that decorate the inner courtyard and the chandeliers.
The two-color scheme gives maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was enough to bet on the principle that white reflects more than dark, which absorbs the rays of the sun.
The Casa Battlo, which was inscribed in 2005 on the UNESCO World Heritage Fund, can be visited by anyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and splendid apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous designer.
They continued the visits because they found that it was a profitable business and they expanded the visits to the common areas and the attic including the roof terraces.
The entrance to the monument is really cheap and costs 16.50 euros; students, retirees, groups and tourist card holders get 20 percent off.
The sum is still above the entrance fee to the other Gaudi buildings in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic turrets, you must quickly find a companion among the building's inhabitants and visit the house completely.
How to choose a mattress and a bedside table: women have different criteria than men.
Not a flashy frame, but rather the quality of the bed surface, so the mattress and the bed frame provide a real base for a good bed.
They must, of course, complement each other harmoniously to please a particular user.
During the selection several factors are decisive:the weight, height, age, health status and sex of the owner.
The type of interior in which the mattress and the door frame are to be placed is also important.
Typical example?
For example, in a country house where there is no continuous sleeping, latex mattresses are not suitable because they "warm up" slowly.
They are also heavier than standard polyurethane mattresses.
They need to be turned over frequently.
If they also do not have sufficient ventilation channels in the core and if they are also on a solid board, they retain moisture.
Habit is also a factor in the choice.
A person who spends his time abroad where very thick mattresses with a soft coating are frequently used will hardly feel comfortable on a low, hard surface.
"That's how all the hockey players who come back from the NHL complain that they can't sleep there".
"For their tired shoulders, feet and ribs, they needed mattresses with a soothing layer of lazy foam".
"Such mattresses are also recommended for people who suffer from diabetes or have a nervous system disorder, which makes it difficult for them to receive information from the joints and skin", explains Sylva Adamczikova, a specialist in upholstered furniture.
That is why the lazy foam mattress has been so popular with hockey players and other customers for some years.
"Today everything is working well, Tempur, the Italian Magnifex and also the Czech Tropico have suitable mattresses.
You don't have to be an NHL guy to appreciate a lazy foam.
This "miracle" just works.
It optimizes its rigidity and shape according to the heat absorbed or adapts to the heat of your body.
Nothing presses you and you don't turn around in the night like after a tough game.
You just sleep better.
Lazy foam also works as a protection against the spores.
To choose a mattress for your height, add the length of the feet, which is about 21/34 cm.
So a man and a woman who are both 6'2" tall need a bed that is 6'2" tall.
The minimum width for each bed for a two-seater should be 90 cm, or 180 cm in all.
For single beds, single beds for example, it is recommended to take at least 120 / 140 cm.
It's convenient for visitors.
'However, there is a simple rule for the width of the bed: when you are lying on your back you should place your hands comfortably with your elbows slightly bent.' Helena Prokopova, President of the Association of Mattress-Builders and Decorators, who has been working for several years on the problem of healthy sleep and the ergonomics of furniture and teaches this in specialised schools.
For a double bed each person needs his own bedside and mattress, so be careful when buying to choose the mattress height.
Otherwise you will only have to mount the bed frame at different heights and this is not feasible on all bed frames.
The minimum height of foam mattresses should be 14 cm, spring mattresses at least 15 cm, and the minimum height of the form and airing layer should be 3 cm.
"When you touch or sit on the mattress, you must not feel the springs", warns Héléna Prokopova.
Each mattress requires a specific type of mattress.
The summer bed, when the mattress and the bed frame are joined like Siamese sisters, has no place in the bedrooms.
The mattresses are very badly worn; they must not be washed, which is commonly done nowadays.
And since during the night we normally sweat 0.2 to 0.75 litres of sweat it is clear that after 5/7 years, the mattress begins to resemble a large (and clogged) sieve.
So experts refuse to advertise a 25-year life span for a mattress or a lifetime warranty.
But all to his but.
And here is a tip from the sellers: for a 120/140cm mattress, do not use a mattress cover, hygiene or washing, but use a protective mattress that you can easily remove and wash.
And even if nowadays it is common to manufacture coatings with zipper for the whole assembly, that is to say that after the opening we have two parts (for washing and the size of the washing machine is very important!) otherwise the handling for the large models (and for only one person) becomes a fight between a light weight and a heavy weight on a ring.
You have a hard board in your bed instead of a bed frame?
I never will!
Maximum for a bed for visitors for one night only.
However, equip the board (if there are no such) with ventilation holes and use the spring mattress with a minimum height of 15 cm with bag springs (German Taschenfederken) and a ventilation layer.
A polyurethane mattress should not be part of a bed of this type.
For single-position flange mattresses with 14/18 flanges, latex or sandwich mattresses (perhaps a combination of latex and coconut) are ideal, but it will always be better for you to have a mattress with more than 28 flanges and above, where the flanges are folded in the lower part of the kidneys and thus it is possible to regulate the stiffness.
For multi-position mattresses, do not use a spring mattress as it does not respond to changes in position.
In addition to the rigidity adjustment of the blades, a so-called shoulder cradle can also be installed.
This is a special bonding of the lamellae that allows the lamellae to be pressed or tilted so that the sleeper's shoulder "integrates" well.
For men who have "shoulders as wide as the back", this is a very important thing.
This is already being considered by mattress manufacturers who have begun to use a shoulder-softening area for the "male" mattresses.
But they also think about women - they offer them a softer surface in the hips again.
For the most demanding customer there are winged or padded caps with what is called a multiforce suspension.
The pressure spreads to more points and the tension decreases.
But of course, be careful, as soon as you use a bad pillow (big and inflated) on a good mattress and mattress, the "plus" disappears.
The basic rule is a simple pillow: the pillow should support the head and its tips should reach only the shoulders, so that the muscles of the shoulders can rest.
The recommended size is 50X60 cm which Scandinavians by example prefer.
When lying on the side, the pillow should level (with the shoulder pad of the headboard or the softened area in the mattress) the height of the shoulders.
Modern mattresses still have something in common with the first ones made of straw and herbs.
Manufacturers still use natural materials or mixtures.
The trend is also towards organic mattresses.
The petroleum-based raw materials from which polyurethane is produced are replaced by natural oils, such as soybean oil.
Almost all known manufacturers use soybeans.
"The Bio label for the mattresses means that the heart is made from natural products", explains Petr vasicek of Tropico Plus.
Natural materials are also used for mattress coverings, one of the first being aloe vera.
But you can add microcapsules that develop scents of the forest or lavender.
There are differences between men and women.
While the birch plant extract for the mattress coating absorbs heat and cools the body, "cooling" the man, the coatings "warm" the woman.
Red pepper extract speeds up blood circulation and is therefore warmer for the weaker sex.
What are your current favorites?
Mattresses made from cold foam (it has more pores with a disturbed cellular structure so more breathable than standard polyurethane and has more elasticity.
The combination of different rigidities of the cold molds gives polyzone mattresses that know precisely where the head, lower back and feet are.
You will pay for a quality mattress from 7000 crowns and more.
Those characterized by their health parameters have less VAT and are taken as instruments for health.
In the Czech Republic, Gumotex has taken the top spot.
Saving for mattresses and bedspreads is not easy.
Special promotions from manufacturers or producers may occasionally be available for two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, Magniflex offers Duofreeze mattresses with Memory foam sewn into the cover for 11990 crowns.
Of course, you can get the second one for free.
The era of lazy or viscoelastic foams with an open cell structure and a large thickness began with the Tempur material at a "cosmic" rate.
It started as a matter for NASA because the astronauts were subjected to the start of enormous load factors.
Temperature melts in the heat and hardens in the cold.
It therefore adapts perfectly to the warm human body and distributes optimum pressure to it.
It is therefore ideal for sleeping disorders and for an increase in comfort during sleep.
Viscoelastic foams are used not only for mattresses but also for health products, such as special foot cushions that relieve the legs and the venous system.
Czech manufacturers use for example EucathermC or Twinsaver foam or similar type.
Tracking devices are increasingly being requested by parents who wish to monitor their children.
Fear for their child has more and more people thinking about monitoring their child through a GPS.
The system, originally designed to track cars, can also be used to track people's movements and help in some cases, such as the case of little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently the size of a matchbox but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of little Anicka has moved many people and they have started looking for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their privacy.
"We try to tell everyone that this is not spying but just another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy", says Petr Pilin from the company MAcro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking devices on the Czech market.
"I admit there may be instances of misuse of such devices, such as putting them in the bag of someone who is unaware, but I have not yet encountered such instances".
"The majority of people are customers who actually buy the product for safety reasons", Pilin adds.
He said that children should always know what the "box" is for and how to use it in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bockova points out that if a child does not want to wear such a thing, he will get rid of it.
'And even the smallest ones can show great creativity when it comes to purposely getting rid of something when they don't want to be under control.'
"Cell phones, which can cut themselves off like these tracking devices, have already made parents wait a long time", says Bockova.
She said that the fact that this type of device can help in the event of aggression is very questionable.
"If it's a planned kidnapping, the perpetrator will make sure the child doesn't have an electronic device that can locate him".
"Actually, it's the phone".
"As soon as tracking devices are developed, they (criminals) will also go looking for them because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign".
"In such cases the criminals will always be ahead of the police", says the psychologist.
She admits, however, that such devices can help in the case of unprepared aggression by a pedophile.
Robert Cech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, says that having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an assault.
'The apparatus may be so configured that it is in regular operation after a specified period.'
"In the event that the device is destroyed, the last position of the person concerned remains".
'The more expensive devices also have a tiltmeter that immediately signals the position of the person who has slipped and is found lying motionless,' says Cech.
He believes that smartphones equipped with a navigation system can offer a similar service after formatting it with a special software.
The problem with current tracking systems is that they are either a device similar to those that are worn on pendants the size of a matchbox or the smallest telephone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina of the Macro Weil company, this is why tests are currently being conducted to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that any attacker will not be able to recognize the tracking device".
"Or he will find out after a while, which will give the police a little more time", he adds.
Whether the tracking device is developed in the form of a bracelet or a pendant, it will always use the same technology as for tracking cars.
It is a combination of positioning systems using GPS (commonly used in car navigation) and a feature in a mobile phone that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
The army has enough blasting cord to circle the Czech Republic with, but it can only last two years.
The army bought 274 miles of ropes used for explosives.
Last year, the Department of Defense purchased 224 kilometers of it.
So the army has reserves for 225 years.
The problem is that the life span of the strings is two to four years at most.
The army bought some detonator cords from the STV Group for 40 million crowns.
The General Staff gave as a reason for the purchase of a huge amount of detonating cord MF DNES that the soldiers use 60 km per year.
According to the calculations of the reserve to be held by the army's pyrotechnicians, with whom the Ministry of National Security and Emergency Situations has been in contact, it appears that even generals, officers with a command, secretaries or household personnel should have an annual exercise in explosives.
Alexander Vondra, Minister of Defence and Vlastimil Picek, Commander of the Army are no exception.
