To this day I benefit from the contacts I have made through the competitions.
The franchise sale of his hotel helped Lukas Pytloun to win the prize for the best individual entrepreneur.
The winner of last year's Individual Entrepreneur competition was Lukas Pytloun, a 28-year-old entrepreneur.
His journey to success is like a movie.
Lukas Pytloun was a traveler.
And abroad, he realized that Liberec lacked a quality accommodation facility at a reasonable price.
With his savings from what he had earned while working abroad and with the help of a bank loan he bought a small building of 5 apartments half demolished.
This was a courageous move, since he was still a student in his 30th year of graduate school.
"The quality of accommodation in our area and the price made me want to do something", says Lucas Pytloun.
He began renting the first apartment rebuilt to foreign workers.
He reinvested the profits in the building, which he converted into a 54-bed guesthouse.
Since then, his entrepreneurial activity has allowed him to open in Libérec 4 pensions, two stylish restaurants and two hotels with a total capacity of nearly 300 beds of all categories of accommodation.
The most comfortable of these was until very recently the four star Pytloun design hotel.
This year, another one of the same quality arrived.
"We just signed a contract with a hotel in Ostrova U Tise where we sold our franchise concept and other candidates for the Pytloun hotel franchise have shown up", the number 1 of entrepreneurs last year.
"And for the sale of the licence for the operation of a large-scale hotel, the win in the entrepreneur of the year competition has served well", Pytloun adds gratefully.
The victory brought him more popularity and to be known in Liberec and its surroundings.
"People recognized me in the streets, often congratulated me, and I must say, it was very pleasant", he recalls.
He recommends participation in this contest to all who strive to do something.
It's not necessary to win, but any opportunity to be seen is good.
He says that he still uses his contacts and knowledge that he could not have obtained otherwise.
"I started to have regular business contacts with those I met through the contest.
He said the fame of the success had an impact on the employees as well.
And he's about 70.
"What I see in them is loyalty and pride in having committed themselves to something that has been generally recognized".
"This is not, and far from, the only result of my personal work, but the result of good work by all of us together.
"Only my name is being pushed forward", Lucas Pytloun modestly said.
I wish my successor a better year than the one we had in Farmet.
The euphoria of victory was quickly replaced by the effects of the crisis.
Thanks to the winner's sense of purpose Farmet has the worst moments behind him.
The person who came to Slovansky Dum to collect the prize for the first place in the competition for the Firm of the Year organized by Vodafone last year was Karel Zdarsky, the owner of the company Farmet.
The jury awarded him for his efforts to turn a tool shop in Ceska Skalice into a company with a turnover of 100 million kroner.
'I can say that the award has encouraged not only me but also my colleagues and has increased our confidence to fight the competition,' says the winner of last year's competition today.
At the beginning of the history of the Farmet company there was the desire to do something useful.
And so when the state offered Karel Zdrasky's father to rent the small workshop as compensation after the confiscation of property by the communists, he did not hesitate long, refused a career in a firm where he worked at the time, and created a company with some comrades in his father's entourage for the manufacture of plastic baths.
Not long after, they started specializing in vegetable oil presses.
After eighteen years it became the largest manufacturer of automatic presses in Central Europe.
The company became known even to the non-specialized public after the success obtained in the competition through the media.
"Not only did our customers really start to know the Farmet brand better but also the foreign partners who started to realise that they were working with a company that has achieved the greatest success in its home country", says Karel Zdarsky.
But the past year was not just a year of victory in Farmet.
The valuation of the company was based on the economic results of 2008 and partly of 2009.
And 2009 was the hardest year for selling engineering machinery.
At the height of the crisis, which did not really affect the citizens, companies were forced to stop their investment projects and start to limit their purchases of new materials and technologies.
"We obviously didn't escape this situation".
"Turnover fell by 40 percent, and we had to limit our production and even lay off workers", explains Karel Zdarsky.
A viable society must know that from time to time unpopular measures must be taken.
But they have managed the situation correctly and have maintained profitable results even if they were lower than they were before the crisis.
At Farmet, however, they continued to invest in research and development without compromise.
"We built a training and research centre with the endowments, strengthened the company's presence in international exhibitions and won top awards at national exhibitions", says Zdarsky.
All the evidence points to the crisis being behind them.
Business numbers are up and with them the number of employees.
"I wish the new winner this pleasant feeling of victory but in a calm atmosphere", says Karel Zdarsky.
The investigation that removes senseless regulations.
The Absurdity of the Year investigation is now part of the business clan for the fourth time.
Some of the absurd regulations have been removed.
The unfortunate winner of this year's Absurdity of the Year survey was the requirement to bring documents into the offices that civil servants can get online.
More than a third of the 4,000 voters voted for it.
For example, the social services administration required a paper extract from the trade register, whereas the official could obtain it with a few clicks of the mouse.
The investigation changes that.
"The Czech Social Insurance Administration will no longer require the extract from the trade register for the control of insurance payments", said Jana Buranova, spokesperson for the Czech Social Insurance Administration (CSSZ).
To highlight all the regulations and decrees that companies and entrepreneurs have to comply with in the Czech Republic and to delete those that are absurd is the meaning of this contest of the absurdity of the year.
This survey is again this year for the fourth time a part of the business clan organized by Hospodarske noviny and has even greater popularity.
Last year 3,000 voters demonstrated, this year at least 4,000 have voted.
And it is not surprising, there are in our country the most diverse legal obligations that only hinder the company, and,this, more and more.
"We may be the number one tax filing nation in the world", says Karel Havlicek of the Czech Association of Small and Medium-sized Enterprises and Entrepreneurs.
The simplification of entrepreneurship has become a proclaimed goal of all governments in recent years.
The situation in the Czech Republic is not improving at all compared with the rest of the world.
According to the World Bank, the Czech Republic ranks 74th in terms of conditions for enterprise, 8 places higher than last year.
The Absurdity of the Year competition was first launched in 2006 and continues every year under the same scenario.
Anyone can report administrative and bureaucratic absurdities from April to the end of September each year, the last time before the competition closes.
The organiser of the competition then chooses seven candidates for the "antiprix" and lets the public vote during the month of October on the website www.firmaroku.cz/absurdita and on www.ihned.cz.
The Absurdity that receives the most votes is declared the winner.
Until the last inquiry last year, there were about 100 or more precisely 105 regulations and decrees which had lost their meaning.
The comments are sent by the employers but also by the trade unions and the teachers.
Among the "finalists" of the competition, so among the nominees, is the obligation for motorway and highway maintenance vehicles to pay tolls, or for contractors with twenty employees to repaint two offices and two toilets every two years.
The list of the seven proposals is published on the competition website.
The announcement of the competition, which always begins in early November on the Venceslas Square in Prague, is part of a happening in which political and public figures regularly participate.
This year, for example, Eva Svobodova, director of the Association for Small and Medium-sized Enterprises in the Czech Republic, and Petr Kuzel, president of the Chamber of Commerce of the Czech Republic, attended the highlight of the competition.
'Economic prosperity cannot work when the state puts a bridle on the entrepreneurs' legs and for this my aim is to remove, every year, at least three dozen paragraphs which today only complicate the business,' declared Martin Kocourek, the Minister of Industry and Trade.
The effort to repeal absurd decrees is not a blow in the water.
In 2007, what people didn't like was the requirement for entrepreneurs to declare three days before to the office for the individual enterprise at the place where the enterprise is located, the intention to go to an exhibition or a pilgrimage with a stand.
This requirement was removed with the amendment of the Individual Enterprise Act.
The second most popular requirement in 2007, which was to report to the Labour Office a business trip for a foreign employee for 30 days, was abolished with the text of the so-called Green Card Act.
And everything is fine until the third session of the competition.
The absurdity of 2009 was the decree for physiotherapists to have a large mirror in their office, a refrigerator and two automatic scales.
This was changed by order of the Ministry of Health last year - the requirement to have a refrigerator was removed.
A new category rewards socially responsible companies.
Environmental, humanitarian, training and sports projects are assessed.
The new feature of this year's Hospodarske Noviny competition, which has been running for 5 years, is the category called the Responsible Firm of the Year 2010.
The objective of this competition is to support reasonable and fair enterprise.
"We want to support companies that monitor the environmental impact of their business and are socially responsible", says Patrick Bartholdy, regional manager of the mobile phone operator Vodaphone, which is the sponsor and promoter of the contest, as well as the contest for the Rebel of the Year.
For this first year of this subcategory of the 2010 Firm competition, organized by Vodaphone, companies that are not successful with a single long-term objective for the company have registered.
The adventures of each of them are rich in inspiration and an independent article would be worth editing.
Although the object of their enterprise is different from each other, their support and planning activity can be considered as the denominator of their efforts.
In one case, it concerns disabled people and the personal or health problems of their employees.
Among the 14 finalists for the whole of the Czech Republic is the Czech software company Et Netera, which supports the creation of informal sports teams of its employees who then participate in a number of tournaments in different sports disciplines.
Another example of a company responsible for the Pardubice region is the Isolit-Bravo company, which has been the main contributor to the endowment fund for 17 years, which sponsors disabled children.
The old paper mill in Podebrad, which employs more than 70% of the workforce, has been awarded the title of the responsible firm for the Central Bohemian region and has been awarded third place in the region in the firm of the year competition organized by Vodaphone.
In Olomouc, MiRyz Soft, a financial company, won by introducing flexible working hours and even reducing the average working week to 35 hours, without a corresponding reduction in wages.
The jury awarded the prize to the company because it buys primarily from Czech manufacturers, supports local businesses in the surrounding area and is concerned about the environment.
"We try to recycle as much as possible so that our business and administration have the least impact on the environment", explains Miluse Ryznarova, the company's executive director.
The company responsible for IT Enlogit in the Usti region also thinks about the health of its employees and has set up an ergonomic chair and keyboard for each laptop, encourages them to work from home and uses the catering services of a local protected factory for its actions.
"We also support the Man in the Shadow Foundation which helps the local Romani community", says Ondrej Suchy, the company's representative.
At the very bottom is a Karlovy Vary region washing and cleaning company, which also participates in the pension insurance of its employees in the form of bonuses above the standards.
"In our society we contribute to food, transport, upskilling and recreation", says Joseph Strapac of the bruntal construction company Czasch, winner for the Moravian-Silesian region.
All regional finalists in Vodafone's Firm of the Year competition who had completed the questionnaire attached to the registration document and had sent it back to the organiser by 15 August were automatically entered in the category of Responsible Company.
The organiser removed wrong or incomplete answers from the questionnaire.
"If the representatives of the competing firms did not answer the questions, they could not participate in the competition for the firm responsible but were not disqualified from the 'main' competition for Vodafone's firm of the year".
"Independent entries are not possible as this is a subcategory of the main Firm of the Year competition", explains Karel Goldman of the organising agency Bison&Rose.
At the Land Fund in Plzen, the police made arrests during a public competition
In the building of the Land Fund in Plzen, the anti-corruption police made arrests in recent days.
Detectives have handcuffed local contractor and real estate developer G. Lubos.
The applicant sought to manipulate a public tender for the settlement of a claim for restitution in such a way that the proposed land was obtained by a specific applicant.
The latter was to pay Lubos G. half a million crowns.
"At the moment I can only confirm that the police are pursuing a person for insider's crime in the framework of a public tender and competition". Antonie Zelena, the head of the Plzen Prosecutor's Office, told Pravo newspaper, knowing that it is forbidden to provide further explanations because the investigation is ongoing.
The police released the 46-year-old entrepreneur after 24 hours.
How he could influence a public competition is a matter of speculation, given the paucity of official information.
Asked about Pravo, the spokeswoman for the Land Fund, Lubomira Cerna, said that the police actually arrested a man in Plzen at a separate workplace during the public competition.
"It was a customer and not an employee", she said.
The public tender according to Cerna has the real name "Call for Proposals for Land Transfer Rights under the Land Act" and is set up when several candidates for rights are presented.
"These persons are offering, in the context of the call, a higher value of their restitution rights which must be settled before the land value is announced".
"According to the proposed rights, a ranking of the purchasers is set up and the Land Fund then transfers the land to the person who has proposed the highest rights", explained the Fund spokesman.
Lubos G. had, of course, the information concerning the persons who had registered for the call and, as he himself was also a beneficiary because he had bought a large number of rights to refunds, he had proposed to the candidates on the ground not to participate in the competition.
And he probably paid for it by retiring.
Which would explain why he had so much money in his possession at the time of his arrest.
Lubos G. had contacts well above the standards at the FdT (Fonds des Terres).
He was involved in the case of former FdT leader Vaclav Sankot, who was prosecuted for having edited land for which the decision to set up a construction had already been issued.
Mr Lubos G. had obtained land for the construction of public roads, specifically at the place where the access road to the industrial area of Borske Pole was to be built.
Later he exchanged it with the city hall for a building in the historic center of the city whose value is much higher.
The city council was forced to accept because otherwise it would risk jeopardizing the construction by blocking the land.
Households will pay an additional 100 crowns per month for accommodation.
Households will have to pay a surcharge from January not only for all types of energy but also for water and sanitation, heating supplies and in some places rents will also increase.
Families will therefore have to withdraw from their wallets up to 100 kronen a month more than now.
Electricity goes up 4.6 percent, gas up almost 2 percent, in some localities you will have to pay up to a tenth more for water supplies and in many places central heating supplies will also be more expensive.
The increase in electricity consumption for apartment households is expected to be around 100 kroner more per year than at present.
However, all suppliers have reduced electricity prices in view of the significant development in encouraging the manufacture of renewable energies, particularly photovoltaic cells.
Gas increases moderately, but of course at the time when people need it most for heating and therefore have the greatest consumption.
So there is also an additional 100 crowns.
Although electricity and gas prices are increasing throughout the Czech Republic, the change in central heating prices differs from town to town.
The larger municipalities are the ones that plan the price increases.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Kraloce will pay almost 50 krona more per month for central heating from January onwards, while families in Liberec will pay over 1000 krona per year.
For the people of Prague, a 9 percent increase in water and sanitation is being prepared in case the city raises infrastructure rents.
If the rent is not changed, the Prague residents will pay an additional 6.8 percent.
The price in Prague will still be among the lowest in comparison with the whole country.
In Northern Bohemia, where prices are already among the highest, water and sanitation are up 7.4 percent.
For example, rental prices will rise significantly in the 450 thousand apartments for rent from January, that is to say at the end of the regulation.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which owns almost 2500 apartments in Usti nad Labem, decided to increase the number of apartments by up to 100%.
Those who disagree with the new rent increase will be taken to court by the company.
The regulated rents people pay in nearly 300,000 apartments could rise next year by 10 percent.
Czech children get drunk on rum and fern, beer is out of fashion and acts very slowly.
Fernet, rum, vodka and, exceptionally, the best brand of whiskey are stolen from the parents.
These are the drinks that most often bring into the hands of the doctor those who get drunk, who are not yet fifteen years old.
Children who are treated in hospital for a recurrence are no exception.
This is the result of the experience of doctors who encounter cases similar to those in the children's wards of hospitals.
"Beers and wines are out of fashion because it takes time to get drunk".
'The trend is really towards strong alcohols,' says Pravo Ludek Pelikan, Head of the children's department at the hospital in Horovice in Central Bohemia.
"When they manage to sneak a bottle of Pop in the cupboard, it's sometimes whiskey but it's fern and vodka that prevail".
"The vodka has the advantage that they can mix it with fruit juice and not smell it", explains the Head of Department.
Eva Jurinova, spokeswoman for the Motol hospital, also agrees with him.
"It's usually rum or fern".
"It's all the rage today, especially in elementary schools".
"In some cases, it was slivovice that they brought from home", added Jurinova.
According to the Head of Department Pélican, seeing drunk children aged 13 to 14 years old in hospital admissions is a normal phenomenon.
Before working in Horovice last year, he was at Motol where he practiced for ten years in pediatrics, where ambulances brought schoolchildren from the surrounding area completely drunk.
"A girl was hospitalized four times
"She started her career at the age of 12 when she was brought in with 3.5 per thousand of alcohol in her blood plus a mixture of ecstasy", the doctor described this particularly important case.
"She was at the Exhibition Park in Holesovice at a party".
"What is interesting is that it did not seem strange to the mother that her daughter was absent for 48 hours", said the department head in astonishment.
It is precisely the selflessness of parents or their unusual tolerance of their offspring's drinking that is the main cause of the development of alcoholism in children.
However, experts say that children are not considered to be addicts in the strict sense.
"The term alcoholic means chronic alcohol dependence for several years with all the associated phenomena, but not found in children".
"For those who use alcohol repeatedly, it is more a matter of a significantly unfavourable socio-family background", explained the Head of Department Pélikan.
According to spokeswoman Jurinova, about forty drunk children were hospitalized this year until mid-November in the pediatric clinic in Motol.
Only cases with severe intoxication requiring hospitalisation are included in the statistics.
Drunk children who are after emergency care brought home by parents or by the police, are not counted.
Besides the cases of children sitting down and drinking a bottle of alcohol after school, it arouses three seasonal waves that we can expect, according to Pélikan: Witches' Day, New Year's Eve, and the end of the school year.
"Either they drink out of spite after a bad grade or they celebrate the start of the holidays".
"Of course I have experienced on the day of the witches an admission of 7 children drunk at one time", emphasized Pélikan.
The drunken child who spent the night in the hospital in drug rehab under medical supervision is paradoxically in a better position than the one who went home and suffered from "wood-fever" the next day.
Morning headaches caused by dehydration and glucose deficiency are relieved by an infusion of glucose and nutrients that the body needs.
"They are better off because they have a great night and then a nice wake-up and nothing hurts".
"They are just amazed at where they are", adds Pélikan, knowing that from time to time this spoils the good mood of the patients at least with the bill to pay for their care.
The cost of ambulance transport and hospital admission in an intensive care unit can be tens of thousands of kroner.
"On occasion, I have applied this as a means of education by telling these children how much their drinking has cost them and that they could spend the whole summer in seasonal work to pay for one night", added Pélikan.
However, he argues that health insurance companies, in their regressive management, which should recover from parents the costs of care, do not treat cases of drunk children.
Two L-159 aircraft are in foreign hands in Spain for the first time.
Two L-159 aircraft out of five in all, for which the Ministry of Defense has exchanged Casa C-295M transport planes, took off Tuesday for Seville in Spain where the aircraft manufacturer Casa-EADS is based.
This is the first time that aircraft of this type have become the property of someone other than the Czech army.
They have, however, been abroad for training or demonstration flights.
These are the two-seater versions of the L-159T1 which were until now in service in the Czech Army and were in flying condition.
The remaining three aircraft are single-seat versions of the L-159.
They are currently stationed at Aero Vodochody and the commercial intermediary - the Omnipol firm - took them into account last week.
According to Jan Pejsek of the press department of the Ministry of Defense, the physical departure of the Vodochody planes is currently unknown.
'The L-159 single-seaters planned for the exchange were taken from long-standing aircraft stockpiles without causing additional costs or investment for the Ministry of Defence.'
"The two-seater L-159 T1 was exchanged in the state", said Pravo Pejsek.
He added that the army will not remain without two-seater as the ministry signed in May 2009 with Aero Vodochody an agreement worth 200 million crowns for the transformation of four unused L-159 single-seaters into two-seaters.
The Army took delivery of the first aircraft in July, with the second due for delivery later this year.
According to Pejsek EADS has committed to introduce the aircraft in the equipment of certain countries of the Alliance.
"The contract clearly states that the L-159 aircraft are being purchased by EADS and will be used for the training of pilots from NATO member countries".
"It is therefore up to the individual to determine how to achieve this", said Pejsek.
Hospodarske noviny announced some time ago that the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
The exchange of five L-159s for one Casa aircraft and the purchase of three other aircraft for 3.5 billion crowns was approved last year by the government of Mirek Topomanek.
The Ministry of Defence did not launch a tender and contacted EADS directly.
The defence department argued that the exchange ensures the future export of the L-159 abroad.
The Czech Army bought 72 aircraft from Aero Vodochody and only used 24 of them, wanting to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa planes will likely have legal implications.
The European Commission has, however, brought a case against the Czech Ministry of Defence before the European Court of Justice because the aircraft should have been selected through a European-wide tender and in no case by contacting a manufacturer directly.
The army has already taken delivery of three Casa planes, the last one is due to arrive at Prague Kbely airport in two weeks.
A longer index finger than the ring finger is a sign of low risk of cancer
Men with a longer index finger than an annular finger have a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday in the British magazine Cancer.
It may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our findings show that relative finger length is a simple test for prostate cancer risk, especially for men under 60", proclaimed study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should be screened for prostate cancer, including by combining it with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009 she and her colleagues in Great Britain followed over 1500 prostate cancer patients and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the right index finger shorter than the ring finger.
They were found to have the same risk of prostate cancer as the 19 percent of men with the same finger length.
For those with the index finger longer than the ring finger, however, the risk fell to 33 percent; for men under 60 years of age, the risk decreased to 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers - formed during the prenatal period - indicates, among other things, different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the womb.
A lower testosterone is a longer index.
Previous research has shown that it is testosterone that helps in the development of prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told CTK that he is aware of the study but does not think the link between finger length and cancer is "fully established".
