"Walhalla Rising" is an enigmatic film that you can hate or admire, that has the goal of excitement, enthusiasm and wonder.
It was a traumatic experience.
Mysterious earthworks
The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) has new evidence of a nuclear programme being developed by Syria.
But the country refuses to take a position on this subject, let alone submit to the agency's controls.
On the night of September 5th to September 6th, 2007 at around midnight, at least four Israeli F-15 I fighter jets attacked a mysterious cube-shaped building on Syrian territory.
It is situated on the banks of the Euphrates, and the nearest major city is Dair as-Sur, some 20 miles [30 km] away.
His name appears in the IAEA documents because it refers to the reactor that Syria built apparently with the help of North Korea in a stone parallelogram, hidden in a valley marked by the absence of electricity.
According to a US intelligence briefing from the CIA in late April 2008, the current reactor, known as the nearby town of el-Kibar, is capable of producing plutonium, which would be used in the making of atomic weapons.
However, this technique has been used since the 1950s.
The CIA has released a video presentation featuring blurry satellite images.
Through computer animation, it showed the likely location of each reactor component before the destruction of the plant, which is a miniature copy of the North Korean model of the Yongbyon nuclear power plant.
In addition, she showed photographs of the building nearby, even inside.
It appears that the reactor was about to be put into operation, but it was not yet equipped with fuel rods.
Today, more than three years after the Israeli bombing, we have hardly any more information than then, and even with time the mystery is getting thicker and thicker.
Former US President George W. Bush recently revealed in his memoirs that before the attack, the CIA was sure that Syria had built a reactor at el-Kibar, but had little evidence that the country was developing "an active nuclear weapons program".
Some intelligence officers in Europe prefer to be more cautious about this and only talk about a "presumed reactor", even if they consider the CIA's presentation as "plausible".
They lack hard evidence, and so does the IAEA.
When asked how he ensures that he is dealing with a nuclear reactor, a senior UN diplomat gave only a terse answer in the summer, saying that the IAEA had "sufficient documents to ask questions".
The Syrians certainly hurriedly removed the rubble of the "unused military building" and made a methodical leveling of the ground.
However, in June 2008, a team of IAEA experts led by former chief inspector Oli Heinonen discovered traces of man-made uranium at el-Kibar.
In addition, the IAEA has received satellite images from commercial providers through one Member State showing the immediate aftermath of the attack. These appear to be more telling than those presented by the CIA.
However, these photos are not available on the market because the anonymous sponsor, possibly Israel, acquired them exclusively.
It is therefore impossible for the IAEA to establish their authenticity in an objective manner.
Syria has always maintained that it has never had a secret nuclear programme and that it has not built a reactor.
Damascus claims that the uranium found at the site came from weapons used by Israel.
But the IAEA dismissed that argument after analyzing the particles as implausible.
Since then, Damascus has refused to discuss this issue, as well as the satellite images.
Furthermore, Syria is not allowing inspectors to carry out a second inspection at the Kibar site and is refusing access to the debris of the building destroyed by the bomb.
But even Israel is stubbornly silent.
Confirming the official position, Ehud Olmert, then Prime Minister at the time of the attack, recently said: "We will never comment on this".
The investigation into the case has been dragging on since June 2008 without any result and "is increasingly becoming a serious problem for the credibility of the Agency", as a senior Western diplomat at the IAEA headquarters in Vienna admits, and it is a serious violation of the treaty banning nuclear weapons.
The IAEA believes that to make progress, the existence of the three other facilities which must have "a functional relationship" with the alleged reactor must be clarified.
So far, the inspectors have not indicated what facilities are involved here, what their function is or what they are suspected to contain.
According to information published by the Süddeutsche Zeitung, they are known within the IAEA respectively as Marj as-Sultan, Masyaf and Iskandariayah also from the names of the neighbouring towns.
The independent Institute for Science and International Security in Washington identified these locations and discovered on satellite images a complex near Masyaf that would most likely be one of the suspected objects.
It is possible that it is located in a military base or directly next to it; this is exactly why Syria is refusing access to the three sites to IAEA inspectors.
In Vienna, it is claimed that the Syrians fear that the inspection team are actually spies who are sent on behalf of the United States by the IAEA to spy on military installations.
In fact, it was intelligence provided by American secret agents that drew the attention of nuclear inspectors.
The IAEA has information, including satellite photos, indicating that vehicles have been shuttling between the three sites and the stone parallel to transport substances.
A senior Western diplomat said in Vienna that at least one of the plants could "serve to produce the fuel".
It would have "no indications of sensitive activities", such as enrichment and reprocessing of uranium, processes that are essential to the production of atomic weapons.
This type of reactor is probably powered by unenriched uranium.
Nevertheless, there are at least plausible hypotheses as to the following fundamental questions: where should the uranium have come from and where would the plutonium later be separated for the bomb.
It is not known whether the debris, which could conceal valuable traces, was stored in the three sites.
When the hundreds of trucks loaded with dirt have disappeared, no one will have any information about where the debris is stored.
The IAEA believes it is unlikely that Syria had the al-Tibni salt mine, located only a few kilometres from al-Kibar on the other side of the Euphrates, examined in 1998 to see whether it could be used for the storage of radioactive waste.
Recently, analyzing satellite photographs for the famous Jane's Intelligence Review, former IAEA inspector Robert Kelley linked the photographs to the reactor in question.
However, satellite images show that Syria had begun excavation work at the three suspect sites and moved huge containers when the IAEA began requiring access to these sites.
It may be a coincidence, but it hasn't helped to rule out suspicion.
The IAEA has spent several months developing a plan for inspections in Syria, which would allow the country to preserve any military secrets, and the time involved shows how much interest the inspectors have in this matter.
Meanwhile, Damascus has also ignored this proposal.
A year ago, if Western diplomats in Vienna had not reported the destruction of the reactor, the urgency would not have been raised in this case, says, for example, Glyn Davies, the US ambassador who has been talking for a few months about what is known as special inspections, one of the most powerful means the Atomic Agency has to implement its controls.
The IAEA Director, Mr Yukiya Amano, who had to propose these inspections, has already spoken of "an option to which I am open in the future", but he is still hesitant.
This means carries a huge risk: firstly, it requires a majority in the IAEA Board of Governors and many of the 35 countries represented on it have no desire to see the situation escalate.
On the other hand, as this diplomat who gives to reflect: "What would it be worth, if in the end they find nothing"
