The democratic routine
Support for democracy in Latin America continues to grow, as does support for private enterprise.
Crime has become a bigger concern than unemployment.
And Brazil is seen as more influential than the United States in much of the region.
These are some of the findings of the latest Latinobarómetro survey, taken in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been carried out regularly since 1995, it tracks changes in attitudes in the region.
Two related elements emerge from the results of this year's survey, which was carried out in September and early October.
The first is the rather sunny mood of Latin America.
The second is the increasing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has risen markedly in several countries on the Pacific rim of South America (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has risen from a low of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also increased in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after suffering a sharp decline in output last year.
But only about half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the region, are committed democrats, which puts the regional average lower (see Table 2).
Some 44% of respondents in the region said they were satisfied with the way democracy in their country was working in practice, the same as last year but a sharp increase from 25% in 2001 (Graph 3)
Some 34% said they had confidence in their country's parliament and 45% in their government, the same as last year in both cases; but a sharp rise from 2003 (17% and 24%, respectively).
Ten years ago, economic problems in Latin America shook support for democracy.
If this has held up during the global financial crisis, it is certainly due to the fact that many countries in the Americas have experienced only a brief recession and have enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, a social security system has helped to protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty only increased slightly in 2009 and has fallen again this year to 32 percent.)
But the mood varies considerably from one country to another (see Graph 4).
Brazil's strong economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, translate into a widely shared sense of progress.
This is more rare in Mexico and Central America where the recession has been more severe and where violent crime has worsened.
For only the second time since the survey began, more respondents across Latin America as a whole cited crime rather than unemployment as the most important problem for their country (see Table 5).
About 31% say that they or a close relative have been the victim of a crime in the past year; however, this figure is down from 38% last year and is the lowest since 1995.
A more robust economic performance is reflected in the increased support for private enterprise and the market economy: some 71% of respondents in the region say that private enterprise is essential for development, up from 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
Some 58% believe that the market economy is the only system that will make their country developed, compared to 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela are of this opinion (and 80% support private enterprise), even though their leftist president, Hugo Chavez, expropriates many private enterprises.
Brazil is the largest leader in the region, mentioned by 19% of respondents (compared to 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged from last year) and Venezuela (9%, down from 11% last year).
But the United States is considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and most of Central America, while Venezuela is ranked in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
A dirty vote
No one expected to have a perfect general election in Haiti on November 28.
But it was far worse than the outsiders who wanted to help the stricken and fear-ridden country.
Voting boxes were presented and a new ballot was cast, ballot papers were scattered in the gutters, polling stations were ransacked and intimidation was used to intimidate the electorate.
The polling stations were open late at night.
Many Haitians, including many who were displaced by the January earthquake, wandered the neighborhood looking for places to vote.
Some of them eventually gave up.
A dozen presidential candidates, including several presumed favorites, denounced the fraud and called for the election to be cancelled.
Protests, sometimes violent, broke out across the country.
Nevertheless, Edmond Mulet, the senior official of the United Nations in Haiti, considers the event as "a pretty good election in many ways".
Observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community cautiously stated that they did not "believe that these irregularities, however serious, necessarily invalidated the process".
In other words, the show goes on.
The electoral authority, whose opponents are indebted to René Préval, the unpopular outgoing president, and his candidate, Jude Célestin, is due to announce the preliminary results on December 7.
The second tower is expected in January.
All hope in the election is not lost.
The two opposition candidates, rapper Michel Martelly and former first lady Mirlande Manigat, withdrew from their initial appeal to have the vote declared null.
But there may be problems if Mr. Célestin, who has little or no discernible support among the voters, is declared by the electoral authority to have reached the second round.
With a cholera epidemic raging, and over 1 million earthquake survivors still living in tents, it was feared that the turnout would be overwhelming.
In this case, many Haitians wanted to vote but were prevented from doing so because of the disorganization.
Nearly 250,000 ID cards, required to vote, had not been distributed until shortly before the election.
The stakes are high.
Donors see the election of a popular and legitimate government as an important step in Haiti's reconstruction.
And so, obviously, the Haitians are doing it themselves.
The tip of the foot towards the centre
In the weeks after becoming a sudden widow, Argentina's Cristina Fernández received a wave of public sympathy that boosted her approval rating by 20 points to over 50%, the highest it has been since she was elected in 2007.
However, turning this into a successful campaign for a second term in an election next year may depend on whether or not the visibly grieving Ms Fernández abandons the intransigence of her late husband, predecessor and former political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
And, by the way, the signs are still confusing.
Mr Kirchner, who continued to manage economic policy even after his wife succeeded him as president, used to draw up budgets that underestimated tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
It allowed the first couple to spend the extra income at will.
Ms. Fernández's government lost its majority in Congress last year, on paper.
But the opposition is divided, and the situation has descended into chaos following Mr. Kirchner's death from a heart attack on October 27.
Some of the dissidents in the ruling Peronist movement have joined with Ms Fernández.
But after chaotic sessions (where one lawmaker punched a fellow lawmaker in the face and others accused the government of corruption), Congress does not have to approve the 2011 budget.
"I'm not going to argue", said the president.
Currently, the 2010 budget will be implemented next year, leaving the president even more room to spend at will.
The economy is overheating by a large margin: it is likely to grow by almost 9% this year.
The official rate of inflation is now 11.1%, but many private estimates and union wage claims put the figure at close to 30%.
Mr. Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina feared an economic collapse, has made growth and poverty reduction a priority, rather than controlling inflation.
It refused to deal with the IMF, it harassed the private sector and purged the INDEC, the statistical office, for falsifying official inflation statistics.
Can Mrs Fernández now moderate these policies?
It called for talks between private companies and union leaders.
And his officials say they want to limit pay rises next year to 18%.
The economy was boosted by high world prices for Argentina's agricultural exports.
But inflation eroded the growth boost following a sharp devaluation in 2002.
Perhaps that is why Mrs Fernández is showing signs of wanting to restore Argentina's financial relations with the rest of the world.
This year, the government reached an agreement with the bondholders who had refused a previous forced debt restructuring for which Argentina had not paid its 2001 maturity.
Now Ms Fernández seems to be edging towards an agreement with creditor governments grouped in the Paris Club, to which it owes some $6.7 billion.
The Kirchners have always insisted that this could not involve surveillance by the IMF, as is customary.
But last month, Amado Boudou, the Minister of Economy, announced that the Fund would provide "technical assistance" to design a new national consumer price index, which looks like a prelude to the cleanup of the INDEC.
It is not clear whether Ms Fernández wants to remain in politics beyond the end of her mandate, now that her husband is no longer by her side.
If it does, it needs to win the support of the middle class, among whom kirchnerism is very prominent.
When the Argentines return from their summer holidays in March, the wave of sympathy for her will have returned.
If she wants to win another election, she will have to decide whether or not to silently repudiate many of her husband's policies.
Half an hour to China
Taiwanese voters have moved towards a sort of closer union with the mainland.
What does Taiwan think of its big brother across the strait?
More than 7.5 million voters turned out on November 27, or 70% of those eligible, to elect mayors and city councillors in five urban districts, in what is considered a general assessment of President Ma Ying-jeou.
Mr Ma himself has become a substitute for feelings towards the mainland, having forged groundbreaking business ties, including a partial free trade pact, in the biggest reorganisation of relations with China proper since 1949.
Mr. Ma passed the test, but only by a small margin.
Although his Kuomintang (KMT) party won three of the five city council seats, he failed to win a majority of the vote.
Instead, the Democratic Progressive Party (DPP), which leaned toward full independence for Taiwan, won nearly 50% of all votes for the KMT's 45%.
If this was a presidential election, Mr. Ma would be in trouble.
Since he was elected two years ago, his party's vote share has dropped by about 8%.
For the first time, the DPP attracted voters, even with the KMT in the city councils.
The event unveiled most of the main themes of Taiwanese elections, including raucous campaign trucks and mass rally flags with girls dancing in minimal attire.
An assassination attempt was also made.
Sean Lien, son of Lien Chan, honorary chairman of the KMT, conducted a campaign tour for a KMT candidate on the eve of the election.
A man in the crowd shot young Mr. Lien, purely through the face, wounding him and killing a passer-by.
Strangely, it was not determined whether the shooter intended to harm Mr. Lien or settle a dispute with the candidate.
Anyway, said Tsai Ing-wen, the leader of the PDP, the murder had consequences on the election by directing suspicion on the DPP and turning voters towards the KMT.
Perhaps the biggest winner of the election was China.
It was striking how the question of the continental part itself was absent.
Instead, the candidates competed with plans for public housing and job creation.
Taiwan usually enjoys de facto independence and resents the military threat from China.
Thus, the KMT tends to avoid parading its ties with the Beijing government.
But this time, the DPP also refrained from stirring up anti-Chinese sentiment.
This is the response to a new awareness that Chinese companies are indispensable for Taiwan's economic survival.
Mr Ma, for his part, demanded confirmation as to whether his China policy was acceptable to the Taiwanese majority.
The Beijing government can be expected to continue providing trade facilitation, in line with its strategy to lure Taiwan back to the fold.
China has wasted no time in sending a negotiator to Taipei to organize a summit on investment protection and medical cooperation.
It would also like to see political integration, but let us start at the beginning.
Better to wait for that after the 2012 presidential election.
The DPP has reinvented itself anyway.
Two years ago, it was in a bad place: its former leader, Chen Shui-bian, was sent to prison on corruption charges.
President from 2000 to 2008, he was a provocateur in favour of explicit independence.
But a new generation of moderates has emerged under Ms. Tsai's leadership and the PDP is doing everything it can to attract professionals and young people.
Ms. Tsai was hailed as a DPP candidate for president, like Su Tseng-chang, who served under Mr. Chen.
Their party is doing its best to show that it too can engage with Beijing.
Ms Tsai announced plans for a panel of experts to act as a point of contact between the DPP and China, provided that their talks could take place without preconditions.
Ms. Tsai tells the Taiwanese public that her party presents a "trustworthy alternative" to Mr. Ma's hasty approach to China.
Mr. Chen seems exasperated by this change.
In a statement released from his cell, he said that the PDP candidates would have achieved better results if they had insisted that Taiwan is a separate country.
He even ordered Mr. Su, a pragmatist, not to run for president.
Even without Mr. Chen's intervention, the DPP will have a hard time choosing between its potential candidates.
The KMT needs to do some soul searching.
Mr. Ma's ratings were low; despite a booming economy, the KMT candidates did not want to campaign with him.
Its unpopularity seems to be largely due to unemployment and the widening gap between rich and poor.
A KMT spokesman says his office and local branches will be redesigned.
The good results of the PDP suggest that Taiwan's support for rapprochement is limited.
At the same time, most Taiwanese see economic integration with China as inevitable.
According to leading columnist Antonio Chiang, "the point of no return has already passed".
Grammy nominations: jazz singer Esperanza Spalding is a surprise selection in the "best new artist" category
Perform at the request of a president, and the people are obliged to take note of it.
Esperanza Spalding, the 26-year-old jazz bassist and singer hand-picked by President Obama to perform at his 2009 Nobel Peace Prize ceremony, marked one of the surprises at this year's Grammy Awards with a high-profile nomination in the "best new artist" category.
Considering that Spalding has been a well-known figure in the jazz scene since his 2008 album, "Esperanza", the nomination remains a bit of a mystery but is consistent with the Grammy Awards rules that an artist must not release more than three albums before recording; this "establishes the public identity of that artist".
Her ambitious 2010 album, "Chamber Music Society", certainly marked a step forward and, given her slightly engaging vocal style, deft pop and funk hand and Latin influences, it is possible to draw at least a dotted line at Spalding compared to Norah Jones's meteoric success in 2003, the closest equivalent for Grammy voters considering jazz productions in this category in recent years.
Elsewhere, Grammy voters rightly honored Vijay Iyer Trio's "Historicity" in the "instrumental album" category, a turn on the invigorating thrill of a record that was a top favorite last year.
Among these songs, "Moody 4B" by veteran saxophonist James Moody and "Positootly" by keyboardist John Beasley will be in competition.
Trombone Shorty, a favorite of the New Orleans crook and a frequent guest on HBO's "Treme", was honored in the contemporary jazz category; which also leans heavily toward a certain fusion with the albums of Stanley Clarke, John McLaughlin and Jeff Lorber.
The steampunk-savage Darcy James Argue's Secret Society earned some well-deserved accolades in the big ensemble category; competing with the rich chamber-jazz of the Billy Childs Ensemble and the eternal adventurer Dave Holland whose octet's live album Pathways was a fine example of the bassist's democratic hand as a bandleader.
Grammy Award nomination: Michael Daugherty and Steve Mackey lead in the classical categories
The classic nominations for the 53rd Annual Grammy Awards feature a mixture of landscapes by musicians and composers from around the world.
Leading the nominations are Michael Daugherty's "Deus Ex Machina" for piano and orchestra, with five "yeses", and Steve Mackey's "Dreamhouse", an electric orchestral work, with three "yeses".
Among the nominees with ties to Southern California is Estonian composer Arvo Pärt for his Symphony No. 4, "Los Angeles", a work that was commissioned by the Los Angeles Philharmonic Orchestra and opened the Walt Disney Concert Hall in 2009.
The Madolin Concerto by Los Angeles-based composer Avner Dorman is also in the running for an award.
The classical nominations are divided into 13 categories covering orchestral, opera, choral and solo recordings.
A category for the Classical Producer of the Year featured five nominees: Blanton Alspaugh, David Frost, Tim Handley, Marina and Victor Ledin and James Mallinson.
The nominations for the classical album are Bruckner's Symphonies #3 and 4 from the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra; Daugherty's "Deus Ex Machina" and "Metropolis Symphony" from the Nashville Symphony Orchestra; Steven Mackey's "Dreamhouse" from the Boston Modern Orchestra Project and Synergy Vocals; "Sacrificium - the Art of the Castrati" featuring various artists; and Verdi's "Requiem" from the Chicago Symphony Orchestra and Chorus.
In the opera category, the nominees are "Lulu" by Berg from the Orchestra of the Royal Opera House, "Marc Antonio e Cleopatra" by Adolf Hasse from Ars Lyrica Houston; "L'Amour de Loin" by Kaija Saariaho from the Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester Berlin; "The Enchanted Wanderer" by Rodion Shchedrin from the Orchestra and Choir of the Mariinsky Theatre; and "Ivanhoe" by Arthur Sullivan from the BBC National Orchestra of Wales.
The composers in the running for the Grammy Awards for Contemporary Composition include Pärt for Symphony No. 4, Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina", Hans Werner Henze for "Appassionatamente Plus", Magnus Lindberg for "Graffiti" and Shchedrin for "The Wanderer Enchanted".
Pärt's Symphony No. 4 was premiered at Disney Hall in January 2009 in a performance recorded by the Los Angeles Philharmonic Orchestra, conducted by Esa-Pekka Salonen.
The approximately 30-minute piece is called "Los Angeles" and is dedicated to former oil tycoon Mikhail Khodorkovsky, who is imprisoned in Russia.
Dorman's "Mandolin Concerto" was nominated for its instrumental solo performance with orchestra.
The Los Angeles composer said he was writing the 15-minute piece specifically for mandolin player Avi Avital, who played the concerto with the Metropolis Ensemble, based in New York.
"I wrote it using Middle Eastern sounds and a lot of North African scales and rhythms", Dorman said in a telephone interview.
Orchestra conductor Pierre Boulez, 85, received a nomination in the orchestral performance category for conducting the Chicago Symphony Orchestra in a recording of Stravinsky's works.
Instrumental soloists who received a nomination included pianists Nelson Freire and Marc-André Hamelin; organist Paul Jacobs; violinist Julia Fischer and harpist Sarah Schuster Ericsson.
This year, there are only nominated vocalists-soloists; they are Anne Sofie Von Otter, Cecilia Bartoli, Lucie Duchonová, Vivica Genaux and Measha Brueggergosman.
In the classical mixes category, soprano Jessye Norman received a nomination for her recording of "Roots: My Life, My Song"
Temecula's mosque project wins approval from the planning commission.
A mosque project in Temecula received unanimous support from the local planning commission after more than five hours of public witnessing, often passionate.
Critics have attacked the project as promoting both terrorism and traffic congestion.
But the commissioners ruled Wednesday night that the new religious center was in compliance with local laws and would be aesthetically impressive.
"Many good people came to support him: Christians, Jews, Baha'is, you name it", said Hadi Nael, president of the Islamic Center of Temecula Valley, speaking Thursday morning.
"I'm proud of it as an American citizen".
"This shows that justice has been done".
"The opposition is really minimal", he added.
"They just have very loud voices".
"We have good people in this valley".
The session started at 6 p.m. and lasted until almost midnight with, for the most part, people voting for or against the center, with speaking time roughly evenly distributed, according to the Press-Enterprise.
The debate continued on the newspaper's website.
"There is no more America", wrote one commenter.
"It's another planet of apes with Miss Liberty dead in the sand".
"America has fallen".
Planned Islamic centers have also sparked protests in other parts of the country, including at Ground Zero, the site of the September 11, 2001 attacks in New York City.
Imam Mahmoud Harmoush has denounced violence in the Temecula Valley.
Her congregation of about 135 families has coexisted unencumbered in Riverside County for years but she wanted a space bigger and better than the warehouse she rented on a shared property with a water filtration system manufacturer.
The new 24,943 square foot mosque in Mediterranean style architecture would consist of two minarets and rise 43 feet high.
It would occupy a 4.32 acre site on Nicolas Road about two miles east of Chaparral High School.
Opponents can still appeal against this project to the city council.
A microbe that can tolerate arsenic raises the possibility of new life forms on Earth, or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacterium, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, is broadening the field to find new forms of life on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Although researchers have discovered the unusual bacterium here on Earth, they say it shows that life has possibilities beyond the major elements that have been considered essential.
"This organism has a double capacity".
"It can be grown with either phosphorus or arsenic".
"That's why it's very special, even if it's far from a truly 'strange' life form", said Paul Davies C. W. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report in Thursday's online edition of the journal Science.
Six major elements have long been considered essential to life - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, and sulfur.
But researchers have discovered that the bacteria, discovered in Mono Lake, California, is able to continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
"We are wondering what is still possible", said Ariel Anbar D. of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
The discovery is important in the search for life beyond Earth because researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what life is like, Anbar says.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss it, which did not disclose the details of the find, generated widespread speculation on the Internet that the report might reveal the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
That was not the case.
The discovery "shows that in other planetary environments organisms may be able to use other elements to trigger biochemistry and that the 'standard' set of elements, which we consider absolutely necessary for life, may not be fixed", commented Professor Charles Cockell of the Institute for Planetary and Space Science Research, Open University, Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell wasn't part of the search team.
"This work is new because it shows the substitution of one element for another in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure", added Cockell.
It was not a chance discovery.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Institute of Astrology, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, so she speculated that a microbe exposed to both substances might be able to substitute for one another.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is very similar to that of phosphorus".
"As a result, it is difficult for organisms to distinguish these elements separately".
"But arsenic is different enough that it doesn't work exactly like phosphorus; it gets inside and, in a way, rubs off the work of our biochemical machine", Anbar explained.
The researchers harvested the bacterium known as GFAJ-1 and exposed it to increasing concentrations of arsenic to which it was able to adapt and grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that a form of life using arsenic may occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea that phosphorus could replace arsenic was not new; but there was never any evidence that it could work.
Arsenic was more common in the early stages of Earth's existence, she says; so researchers have hypothesized that early life forms may have used it.
This suggests that there could be other ways of forming life, not just the way life on Earth was formed in the beginning", said Foster, who was not part of the Wolfe-Simon research team.
The research was funded by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
The last two stolen show dogs were found in Compton.
The other two show dogs from four robberies outside a Bellflower motel have been found, the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department announced Thursday.
The four show dogs - two Akitas and two Welsh Pembroke Corgis - disappeared on Tuesday when someone stole the Chevrolet Express van in which they had spent the night outside a Bellflower 6 motel, authorities said.
Two of the dogs were recovered Wednesday afternoon and the other two were found late Wednesday evening, said Steve Whitmore, the spokesman for the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department.
"The good news is the dogs are fine", Whitmore said.
"They're in good shape".
"They have been returned to their rightful owners".
Whitmore declined to say precisely where the dogs were found, in what neighborhood and under what circumstances.
"An investigation is underway".
"We don't want to say", Whitmore said.
"We follow orders".
The dogs' owners, Kristina Rickard and David Peek, could not be reached for comment Thursday.
They were reunited Wednesday afternoon with their two Akitas at a county animal shelter in Downey.
Sheriff's deputies found the van and the two dogs separately in Compton.
The Akitas - Trace, a 3-year-old male, and Didi, a 10-month-old female - were safe and sound, authorities said.
But Bunny and Peter, the corgis that Rickard and Peek had planned to show at regional dog shows this week on behalf of Japanese dog owners, were missing until their discovery Wednesday night.
Peek and Rickard, who live in Redding, are in town this weekend for the AKC/Eukanuba Long Beach Nationals, where they were supposed to present Trace.
The other dogs were expected to compete in other events scheduled in the days leading up to the "AKC/Eukanuba" exhibition, Peek told the Times on Wednesday.
Southern California is one of the stops on the couple's nearly month-long dog exhibition tour.
Monday night, Peek and Rickard checked into the motel.
They often stay in motels and park their van outside, right by their bedroom window.
They took three other dogs - a Boxer puppy, a Parson Russell terrier and a Breton spaniel - who stayed with them in the motel room.
But they left the Akitas and the corgis, with the thicker fur, in the van where it would be cooler.
They opened the windows a little, so the dogs could get some fresh air.
Peek and Rickard reported the van stolen at 6:00 Tuesday.
Peek said they'd offer a reward to anyone who could lead them to the corgis, with a microchip implanted to identify them.
It's unclear if a reward was given Thursday.
The lion is ready to blush again, MGM's restructuring is waiting for the final court green light
After 18 months of turbulence and uncertainty, MGM finally got the green light to start from scratch.
A federal bankruptcy judge in New York officially approved the plan "pre-packaged" by creditors on Thursday that would wipe out about $5 billion in debt, paving the way for the 86-year-old entertainment company to focus its efforts on producing and distributing movies and television shows.
With Thursday's ruling that the plan meets the requirements of the U.S. bankruptcy code, there are no longer any legal obstacles for MGM to get back on track under the tutelage of Entertainment Spyglass founders Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, who will become the general managers of what will be a lean studio.
The staff will be reduced to about 320 from 400 at the outset.
MGM will not actually emerge from Chapter 11 until JPMorgan Chase has entered into a $500 million credit facility, intended to fund MGM's new operations and productions.
It is currently licensed by the investment bank, which is itself seeking $75 million, and is expected to be funded by mid-December.
The studio's restructuring process began in May 2009 when investment bank Moelis & Co. was hired to advise management on how to place its finances given that it could not afford to pay the interest amounting to $300 million per year.
In August, CEO Harry Sloan was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former Enron CEO and turnaround expert known for his work at Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis and Cooper's attempts to resolve MGM's financial difficulties and satisfy the studio's more than 140 creditors took much longer than expected.
After several months of discussions, the parties agreed at the end of 2009 to put the company up for sale.
However, the auction attracted few bidders, none of whom were willing to pay the extra $2 billion that the creditors were seeking.
In the spring of this year, it was time to start all over again as the MGM team had begun work on a restructuring plan which, after months of disagreement and internal debate, was finally approved by creditors at the end of October.
When MGM officially emerged from bankruptcy in the following weeks, the Moelis and Cooper companies received multi-million dollar bonuses for their work.
Moelis & Co., which has already received $1.2 million, will receive a payment of $9.5 million.
Cooper's companies, which collected $375,000 a month for their corporate management services, will receive a "success bonus" of $4 million.
Barber and Birnbaum planned to revive MGM's production, which had only released one film this year, and to put together an annual list of seven or eight films that would be released from 2012 onwards.
They also intend to co-finance two films based on "The Hobbit", with Warner Bros.
The studio is required to enter into a separate loan of between $265 million and $275 million to finance its share in these two films, which are to be directed by Peter Jackson.
Investor Carl Icahn, who owns about 18% of MGM's debt, attempted to merge the studio with Lions Gate Entertainment, where he is the largest shareholder.
However, recent discussions between the two companies have not led to an agreement.
Toys Tech to keep your gift budget in balance
Although the top contender for this year's most wonderful toy is the iPad, followed, perhaps, by Microsoft's Kinect video game system, both can make a significant dent in your gift budget.
Consider that for the price of an iPad, you can buy five BMX bikes for $99, and that a Kinect game costs the same as 10 classic beaded jump ropes, or about 48 boxes of Play-Doh.
But there are ways to keep your gift budget in balance.
Recently, I visited three national toy retailers - Wal-Mart, Toys "R" Us and BJ's Wholesale Club - to see the electronic toys I could buy for under $80.
Clearly, Moore's Law has evolved, this year's technological toy is likely to have more power; while costing the same if not a little less, compared to last year.
Furthermore, while there are generally fewer new toys associated with websites, two of the most popular of this type, Webkinz and Club Penguin, have more to offer.
And button-battery toys are on the rise, as are rechargeable battery toys.
Here are some suggestions.
(All prices are from Toys "R" Us unless otherwise stated.)
Sing-a-ma-jigs (Mattel, $13 for 3 years and older) are plush toys the size of guinea pigs that sing a note when you press on their bellies.
One pressure equals one note, and one second equals a song.
If you buy more than one, they'll sing in harmony.
Warning: once you start to push, you can't stop.
To combine singing with dancing, Dance Mickey Star (Fisher-Price, $60 for ages 2 and up) is the best choice.
Drawing inspiration from last year's Elmo Live technology, the 14-inch animatronic doll plays turn-based games like Simon Says and can do the moon dance thanks to its innovative articulated feet with wheel lock.
The children who tried the toy used Mickey as a dance instructor while their parents complained of a lack of volume control.
If you're a child of the '80s, you'll remember Alphie, one of the first computerized educational toys.
It's back (Hasbro/Playskool, $40 for 3 and up), with a backpack filled with playing cards questionnaire designed to turn a drive into a session with a self-correcting and valve clipboard.
If you're suspicious when your child holds your smartphone, here are three standalone alternatives.
The VTech Mobigo ($60, for 3- to 8-year-olds) is the cheapest and easiest to use, with a qwerty keyboard, although the games don't educate as effectively as the Explorer Leapster ($70, for 3- to 12-year-olds), it is the first major revision of the Leapster line, with a newer and brighter screen.
None of the versions are compatible with the old cartridges.
Fisher-Price's iXL ($90, 3-7 years) uses an iTunes-like system to offer games and e-books and has an SD card slot that allows family photos to be displayed.
Finally, Scrabble Flash ($30, Hasbro, for ages 8 and up) is a set of five blocks barely bigger than a matchbox, each with its own LED display.
The goal is to form words by placing the blocks in a line before the time runs out, which is ideal for an impromptu spelling bee.
More and more, toys have a sort of online connection.
Based on their presence in toy stores alone, the two biggest are Webkinz and Club Penguin.
To buy your child a pet online from Club Penguin, for example, you can get a Disney Penguin Club 2"Mix 'N Match Figure Pack, $5 for ages 6 to 12 years) that includes a hidden code-marked coin.
When you redeem the code online, your child gets enough credit at the Club Penguin store for two items of their choice.
It could be roller skates or a pet Puffle toy.
Slightly larger than the hair on the end of your toothbrush, the Hexbug Nano ($10 for ages 5 and up) is the latest button-powered micro-robot.
The fake beetle is moving rapidly on 12 vibrating silicone sticks in random directions.
It's fun to make a maze of blocks to see if she can find her way through.
It is also solid.
Ours has withstood a fall from the kitchen table and even a momentary pass in our dog's mouth.
Bringing a softer side to policing in China
Tang Shenbin was walking a city square like a city sergeant in training by severely inspecting his nerve charges, issuing low-pitched orders with military authority.
He wanted the female members of the chengguan - the imposing officers of public order in China, feared and despised for their arbitrary repression and penchant for violence - to convey a certain impression to a group of onlookers.
"Stand up straight!"
"Be sharp!"
"Show them", he said, "what pretty girls look like".
Four teenage girls in white gloves, identical olive-colored jackets and trousers, stood on their guard.
Four pairs of black high-heeled shoes, lined up in a row.
Four neatly trimmed hats with hair on the top tied with a blue and white striped knot.
"Personally, I think they have average appearance", said Mr. Tang, disdainfully.
"The models are beautiful".
More than one government has tried to refresh the image of China's urban inspectors.
One city required all new recruits to have a college degree.
Guangdong Province has traded in the gray-green uniforms for a blue that is supposedly more engaging.
Wuhan, in central China, replaced the down-eyes with the strong way: in 2009, a report reported that 50 officers surrounded an uncontrollable snack cart by throwing black eyes, firmly for half an hour, until the colporteur packed his things and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 people in Chengdu, has chosen to do a major imaging operation.
Since 2003, the district has supplemented its urban street police with 13 women, specially chosen for their appearance, their complexion and their young age.
The idea is to give the police a softer, more feminine side.
Unfortunately, even Scarlett Johansson might have trouble getting the eye on this underground urban brigade of China.
And for good reason, the critics will say.
Unlike the police, these officers are only authorized to enforce municipal orders by imposing fines or other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese media portray the news as a different reality.
In January 2008, Hubei provincial inspectors beat a local observer to death after he used his mobile phone to film them dispersing a protest against a landfill.
Last year, a training manual for Beijing police officers, stolen and posted online, described how to effectively defeat criminals without spilling blood.
This year in Shanghai, a watermelon dealer was left with a brain injury after a brawl with five officers.
A violent video game, available for download online, shows trained Chinese inspectors raiding street vendors.
"Chengguan has scarred the government", lamented last year China Daily, a national publication, after yet another controversy over the tactics.
The newspaper called for a "genuinely complete cleansing".
Skeptics say the approach is far from it.
