"Most of the time, it's the audience that starts".
The prosecutors will not charge Senator Ensign
Justice Department prosecutors have dropped criminal charges against Senator John Ensign stemming from a case involving a former campaign aide and his efforts to get a lobbying job for the woman's husband, the senator's lawyers announced Wednesday.
The ruling ends the most serious legal threat facing Mr. Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a possible Republican presidential candidate in 2012 until the scandal surrounding his case made national headlines last year and damaged his career.
Mr. Ensign's office said he was "very happy" with the decision, the result of a year-long investigation.
The senator could still be exposed to disciplinary action by the Senate Ethics Committee.
Mr. Ensign's lawyers said the Department of Justice had "informed him that Senator Ensign is no longer the subject of the investigation and that it does not intend to pursue any charges against him in this case".
The Department of Justice has refrained from commenting on the matter.
The announcement came as a sort of surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Justice Department, who said there was significant evidence that Mr. Ensign conspired to violate a federal criminal prohibition on lobbying.
Interviews, emails and other documents, first released in October 2009 in the New York Times, indicated that Mr. Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, get lucrative lobbying work to gain the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator's affair with her.
Mrs. Hampton once served as treasurer on a campaign for Ensign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political funders to find work for Mr. Hampton and then defended their rights after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them, according to the documents and interviews.
Since Mr. Hampton had recently been an associate of Mr. Ensign, he was prohibited by law for one year from lobbying his former employer or the Senate as a whole.
Ethics experts have argued that the unusual agreement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were close friends before the case, appears to contradict the so-called revolving door lobbying ban.
From the evidence that has been made public, "there appears to be prima facie evidence of a conspiracy to rape and substantial violation of the revolving door law", said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients of a government investigation.
Although the department's judge declined to explain the reasoning that led to the decision in the Ensign case, Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department appeared to be wary of political prosecutions after a number of high-profile setbacks by its public integrity section, including last year's decision to drop charges against former Senator Ted Stevens for failure to prosecute.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take up arms, said Melanie Sloan, the executive director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, an advocacy group that has received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"This basically says high-ranking government officials can now assume the laws don't apply to them", she added.
Paul Coggins, Mr. Ensign's lead attorney, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a DOJ prosecutor on Monday and a follow-up call the next day, telling him that the DOJ was not seeking charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign's legal team had cooperated with prosecutors in an attempt to persuade them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement Wednesday, "had acted in accordance with the law".
Mr. Coggins declined to elaborate on the legal arguments he made to the prosecution.
"I'm not comfortable going into the details of my discussions with the Department of Justice, except to say that we think they made the right decision", he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to drop an investigation following an independent complaint by the ethics group, arguing that the $96,000 payment by Mr. Ensign's parents to the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The election commission said they didn't have enough evidence to prove the money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a major Nevada corporation that has long supported the senator, is a company that Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find lobbying work for.
An email sent in December 2008 showed that, after the company had welcomed Mr Hampton as a lobbyist, Mr Ensign's Chief of Staff, John Lopez, contacted Mr Hampton and told him that he was "hammering" the Home Office over a contentious issue.
Mr. Ensign also attended a lunch with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada client, Allegiant Air, and asked the Secretary of Transportation to set up a meeting on behalf of the airline after engaging Mr. Hampton to lobby.
When news of the affair broke last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned as the fourth-ranking Republican in the Senate.
After keeping a low profile for several months, Mr. Ensign announced two weeks ago that he intends to seek a third term in the Senate.
In announcing that Mr. Ensign was no longer the target of a criminal investigation, his spokeswoman, Jennifer Cooper, said the senator hoped the ethics committee would quickly follow the example of the Justice Department and end its investigation.
Senator Ensign is looking forward to continuing his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, she said.
Cheshire's appeal will point to Twitter
Half a dozen of them were tapping away in the courtroom rows.
They were sending out horrific reports of witness accounts every minute via Twitter.
In the end, the defense said there were over 140,000 posts about the rape trial and the children tied to their bed in a house that was burned.
On Thursday, the widely watched trial of Steven J. Hayes, who was convicted of murdering three members of the Cheshire family in Connecticut, is expected to reach a formal conclusion where the judge will impose the death penalty, as voted by the jury.
But Mr. Hayes' lawyers have already filed evidence in court that eludes appeals arguments that could occupy the courts for years.
What is provocative is that the intense reporting of the trial - along with the widespread and extensive use of Twitter by journalists - created a "circus atmosphere", a saturation so widespread and instantaneous with incendiary detail that the jury was badly influenced by the passions of the audience.
The request could prompt appellate judges to debate whether new technology requires new rules in courtrooms.
"I have experienced this in this trial; I think there is a real danger that the introduction of new technology into courtrooms is infringing on the individual's rights to a fair trial", said Thomas J. Ullmann, lead counsel for Mr. Hayes.
Trial judge Jon C. Bleue of the state Supreme Court laconically rejected the claims in his ruling last week, saying that the media was "carefully controlled" and that there was no evidence that the jury was motivated by passion.
But that does not seem to be the final word on the matter.
Appeals courts have recognized for decades that media coverage of high-profile cases can raise questions about the fairness of a trial.
In a landmark 1966 decision, the U.S. Supreme Court overturned the conviction of Cleveland osteopath Dr. Sam Sheppard for the murder of his wife, holding that there was a "carnival atmosphere in the trial" because of the media.
The crime is considered by some to have been the inspiration for the television show and movie "The Fugitive".
Some lawyers have said that appeals courts seized to review Mr. Hayes' conviction half a century later may be curious given the argument that new rules may be needed to manage courtroom communications, unthinkable at the time of Dr. Sheppard's case.
"There is a general reason to be concerned about the impact of new media" in high-profile trials, said John J. Donohue III, a professor at Stanford Law School who has studied the death penalty in Connecticut and wrote a report that it was arbitrarily applied.
Professor Donohue says that some appellate judges might be intrigued by the idea that limiting instantaneous communication from courtrooms could allow for fairer trials.
The Twitter case is just one of many described by Mr. Hayes' lawyers that could be debated for years, delaying execution.
The defense lawyers also argue, for example, that Mr. Hayes suffered injury when Judge Blue refused to allow them to test the reactions of potential jurors by showing them macabre crime scene photos during jury selection.
Some of the jurors said they were horrified by the photos of the victims, Jennifer Hawke-Petit, 48, and her daughters, Hayley, 17, and Michaela, 11.
Defense lawyers say they will also challenge the constitutionality of the death penalty and argue that the judge unfairly expelled one of the jurors, who had been critical of the prosecutors, and that he abused pressure for a verdict by making the unusual decision to bring the jury to deliberate on a weekend.
The jurors were not sequestered.
But their arguments about the effect of the intense media coverage of the trial could be the biggest source of interest.
They noted in a challenge to the verdict, filed last month, that the case dominated the media scene in Connecticut and was discussed during the election campaign by the candidates for governor and the U.S. Senate.
They maintained that the computer media kept stoking the flames of the case's emotion.
"The daily rush of tweets from media, cameras and journalists outside the courthouse", the lawyers wrote, "was unlike anything seen before here in New Haven, and perhaps even nationally".
Their focus on Twitter's coverage is controversial.
In interviews, some journalists said that the claim that instant news was more incendiary than slower-moving news releases was a Luddite view that would impoverish the Court's policy governing media coverage of future trials.
But some lawyers said that appeal courts were often attracted by the arguments that social and technological change required adaptation by the courts.
Mr. Hayes' attorneys are insisting on that claim.
In their filing, they refer to the 1966 Supreme Court decision which overturned Dr Sheppard's conviction because of the media coverage of the trial and they said they would invoke the need for new rules for new media.
"This case", they wrote, "represents the Sheppard v. Maxwell of the 21st century".
Can civility bridge the gaps?
After a campaign marked by both vilification and negativity, a modicum of civility has broken out in Washington this week.
Is this a harbinger of genuine bipartisan cooperation moving forward or an illusory moment before the quick return to partisan struggle in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders produced no breakthrough on the big issues to be addressed during the "lame duck" session.
But clearly, there was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two parties as well as about the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each side wanted to score points.
Wednesday's public meeting of the President's Committee on the Budget Deficit was equally civilized, despite the political differences that remain among the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created a mutual respect that transcends the ideological divide; however, it still divides the members.
It is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Both sides are now in a period of testing and testing each other for signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to gauge the limits of public opinion and voter patience for renewed partisan warfare.
That is why the meeting on Tuesday and the subsequent comments of the participants revealed a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and too deep to suggest a rapid change in climate that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it's taxes, spending, health care or duties, the two sides remain miles apart.
Yet the November election had tempered Washington, at least in the short term.
"There's no question that things have changed on the tone", said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
"It's inevitable after the election.
Elections are partisan passions, and then they fade.
It's good".
On some issues, including the agenda for the lame duck session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
The Bush tax cuts are going to expire at the end of the year, and nobody's in favor of that.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all of it, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is possible on extending unemployment benefits, if only because Republicans can't afford to give the impression that they are in favor of tax cuts for the rich, while denying unemployment benefits to the unemployed worker.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, there is more optimism about a possible agreement on the issues raised during the "lame duck" session, with the ratification of the New START pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the lame duck session will not necessarily prevent a better understanding between the two parties when the 112th Congress convenes in January.
Instead, he said, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
"Once the things that need to be done are done, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations", he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared skepticism that civility would lead to genuine cooperation.
"I consider most of what happens between now and 2012 as a pre-show or shadow-boxing compared to the main event of 2012, he said.
The reasons for this are closely linked to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the tea voters who helped create it.
But Republican leaders are aware of the dangers of going too far, they know they have to try to live up to their promises to cut public spending and repeal the new health care law.
These partisan positions are already clear in the initial reactions to the deficit committee's recommendations which include reforming the tax code and raising some taxes, pushing back the retirement age and cutting spending.
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have chosen one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and have, in their words, forced the issue of the deficit onto the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they needed 14 votes in the 18-member committee to issue their plan as an official recommendation, and they struggled to reach that number.
The greatest resistance remains among the elected members of the group, suggesting that there is little motive or willingness to compromise on tax issues, at least today.
Galston foresees two phases in the fight between the White House and the Republicans in Congress.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan confrontations, as Republicans challenge Obama on budget, tax and health care; to be followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would cause the change?
The public opinion.
There is ample evidence that, despite the partisan spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties work together.
If the confrontation leads to a deadlock, as in 1995, then both sides will watch closely for public reaction.
The one who is judged to be a loser will have to change course and find compromises.
But that would be an optimistic view.
Partisanship and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s and there seems to be a greater ideological divide between Obama and the Republicans in Congress than there was then between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a prelude to a more substantial election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility displayed this week could be enjoyed by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
Leaked US documents describe Moscow as a haven for corruption
The city is controlled by a "Kleptocracy" and some of the bribes and protection money it collects is passed on to the Kremlin, the US embassy in Russia reported in a memo in February.
Police and the Federal Security Service are engaged in huge rackets that help explain the high cost of living in Moscow, he said.
They collect money not only from legitimate businesses but also from organized crime groups.
Each layer of the bureaucracy - what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called the "vertical of power" - takes its share as money moves up the ladder.
The memo, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was posted by Wikileaks on its website on Wednesday.
The note is based on sources whose names have been redacted.
It was written when Yuri Lyukov was still mayor of Moscow, and he is largely held responsible for corruption.
He was dismissed in October by President Dmitry Medvedev but there has been little evidence of cleanup since then.
Lyukhov and his wife, Elena Batourina, who owns a leading construction company, have consistently denied the corruption allegations over the years; and he has won several libel cases over these accusations.
In September, he told a Russian TV channel, when asked about a documentary suggesting he was corrupt: "It's crazy, it's throwaway, it's nothing".
The overwhelming majority of Russians believe that their society is corrupt, according to polls.
But it is unusual to find the information set out in an embassy report; and it is unheard of to conceive that it would be for diplomats of a foreign country to do so.
The direct link between the Moscow city government and crime led some to call it "dysfunctional" and to claim that the government functioned more like a kleptocracy than a government", according to the embassy's note.
"The criminal elements enjoy a 'krysha' (a term used in the criminal world/la mafia that literally means 'roof' or protection) that runs through the police, the Federal Security Service (FSB), the Ministry of Interior (MVD) and the Prosecutor's Office, as well as through the entire bureaucracy of the Moscow City government.
"Analysts identify a three-tier structure in the criminal world of Moscow".
"Luzhkov is at the top".
"The FSB, MVD and militia are on the second level".
"Finally, ordinary criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the bottom".
"It is an inefficient system in which criminal groups fill a gap in certain areas where the city does not provide certain services".
The report says that the FSB is sifting the money of the biggest companies and the police are targeting the smaller ones.
One source, he said, "explained that Moscow business owners understood that it was better to get the protection of the MVD and FSB (rather than organized crime groups) because not only do they have more weapons, more means and more power than the criminal groups but they are also protected by the law".
"That's why the demand for protection from criminal gangs is not as high anymore".
The note notes that although the collection of money is widespread, the protection itself can be uneven; even those who pay are sometimes subject to arrest.
Those who delay in paying their debts are forced to close their businesses for one reason or another.
Medvedev mentioned several times the fight against corruption but admitted little progress.
The embassy memo reports reports men bringing suitcases, probably full of money, to the Kremlin.
"In his fight against corruption, Medvedev depends on bureaucrats", said Georgy Satarov, director of the Moscow think tank Indem, in a recent interview.
