In a dimly lit classroom with shriveled concrete walls of poor quality, the principal of Anlong Veng High School spoke of the man who built it, the last Khmer Rouge leader, Ta Mok.
"Everyone here likes Ta Mok".
"He was a good leader and he cared about his people", said Sreng Kor Ma, 42.
Known as "the butcher" for his brutality when he was the leader of the Khmer Rouge, the commander remains popular in this isolated stronghold of former Khmer Rouge in northwestern Cambodia where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure; and where thousands of former Khmer Rouge soldiers still live today.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, long-standing loyalty to Anlong Veng is finally being called into question.
In April, a local truth and reconciliation forum allowed victims to publicly confront the people who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed a high school textbook that, for the first time, teaches the Khmer Rouge history to the children of its former soldiers.
And in July, a Cambodian court, jointly led with the United Nations, handed down its first sentence against a former Khmer Rouge member, sentencing the former head of the notorious Tuol Sleng torture center, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as "Duch", to 35 years in prison.
This development has increased anxiety among the former Khmer Rouge fighters in Anlong Veng, complicating their efforts to reconcile and reintegrate into Cambodian society.
"There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge but they are powerless to do anything", said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Center, an independent organization that conducts research on the regime.
"For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious but the regime became a symbol of evil".
"The situation is creating divisions within families".
During the Khmer Rouge regime in Cambodia from 1975 to 1979, about 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, disease or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot United government in 1979, the remainder of the regime and its army fled to Cambodia's border with Thailand.
There they launched an insurgency that lasted until the last of the movements surrendered in December 1998.
While Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla from their base in the mountains of western Cambodia and the jungle, Mok Ta prepared a follow-up at Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to defect from the government, culminating in the capitulations of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998 and Ta Mok, who had held out, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the mountains near Dangrek.
He died in a Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Without their benefactors, most of the former Khmer Rouge fighters have sunk into the poverty common to rural Cambodia, and many are nostalgic for the movement.
Although a few elite Khmer Rouge officers kept their local leadership positions in exchange for laying down their arms, these are unskilled farmers at the lowest rank and file.
"These people have received very little follow-up after surrender", said Sok Leang of the Centre for Justice and Reconciliation, which organises public forums across Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They are steeped in the regime's utopian agrarian ideology".
"They were raised in a setting where doing business is a foreign concept".
Sor Lim, 55, joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before settling in 1998 as a poor rice farmer.
"Life under the Khmer Rouge was good", he said.
"Ta Mok feeds everyone".
