The court is expected to start the trial of Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister, early next year.
The court's mandate is to try senior officials and those most responsible for the crimes but it did not say whether it would pursue beyond these four cases.
It would take more than that to calm the fears in Anlong Veng.
The latest media speculation has turned to Im Chaem, 64, a former district chief in Banteay Meanchey province under the Khmer Rouge in the 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Cambodia Documentation Center that she oversaw the construction of the Trapeang Thma Dam, a project where thousands of forced laborers are believed to have died.
Recently, on a hot evening, Im Chaem was returning from work in the field near his wooden house on stilts on a dirt road outside Anlong Veng.
As the sun cast long shadows on the dried grass, Im Chaem refused to discuss her past with the Khmer Rouge.
If the court summons her, she says, she'll refuse to go.
"Cambodia is peaceful and stable", she said.
"If there are more prosecutions, there will be war".
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, also repeatedly warned that instability would occur if the court prosecuted multiple suspects; although experts and historians dispute this.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past", he said.
But facing the past is all that Cambodia needs to do to move forward, says Youk Chhang of the Documentation Center.
"Reconciliation in Khmer terms is to reconnect the broken pieces", he said.
"We need to put these pieces together so we can understand".
The centre produced the first government-approved textbook on the Khmer Rouge, "A History of Democratic Kampuchea, 75 pages".
He distributed it in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the Ministry of Education's history textbooks, designed for high schools, which contained less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As in most of Cambodia, young people in Anlong Veng know little about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city's ties to the regime.
Touch Valeak, a 19-year-old student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new textbook helped students understand an important part of their history.
But his parents were skeptical when he returned home with the book to study.
"My family rejects many parts of the textbook and the court", he says.
"They are wary because they don't know exactly how many people the court will prosecute".
Such resistance has made the process of reconciliation complex and difficult, said Sok Leang.
But the public forums, the manual and the court are starting to have an impact, he said.
Yet the Khmer Rouge retain a powerful appeal here.
High in the Dangrek Mountains, a path, overgrown with weeds and strewn with plastic bags, leads to a black soot rectangle, covered with a rusty tin roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned here on a pile of tires after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a roadside cell phone saleswoman, said she didn't know much about the man who was cremated at the site.
"But he has a great spirit; and many inhabitants go there to pray", she said.
It was Nuom Sothea's birthday and later that day, she planned to walk to Pol Pot's final resting place where she would leave a bunch of ripe bananas in hopes of bringing good luck.
