It is in reality a powerful process simulation software that the German company launched on the market in 2007 with objectives very far from the high-end motor racing.
Called PLM, this powerful computer tool has been used to create assembly lines for the world's manufacturing plants, power stations, high-precision instruments.
The aim is to reproduce, to simulate the product or process accurately before building it in a real way, thus avoiding avoidable defects and costs.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon cameras, Sukhoi aircraft and Nissan's most famous commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens' industrial division, explains that the use of this computer instrument in his Formula 1 factory allowed Red Bull to create and execute "in a few hours, almost in real time", the modifications, changes and improvements detected during races and tests.
