Zapatero and the German Red Line
Berlin opted to stay in the euro, but it set the conditions for the whole Union.
Market tensions have prompted a two-pronged government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero announced new methods of adjustment, ranging from tax reductions for SMEs, regulation of private placement agencies or the abolition of the 426 euros of unemployment aid without professional contribution to the privatization of 49% of AENA, the management of the Barajas and El Prat airports and 30% of the State Lotteries.
On the other hand, Vice President Elena Salgado, with the support of former President Felipe González, joins the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel regarding her responsibility for unlocking the current crisis.
How are these movements to be interpreted?
It should be mentioned that Merkel's position is not a mistake in her communication policy.
On the contrary, it is another constraint in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which clashes with the one of maintaining the old traditions of most of its partners.
In the face of European resistance, speculation is beginning in Germany about three possible ways out of the crisis.
First, a strong euro, integrated by itself, Austria and Holland, among other countries, and the South would leave the monetary zone.
The second is the recovery of the Mark, even though now it seems science fiction, with a very favorable opinion, almost 50% of the population.
The third is a new design of the euro, in line with German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, fiscal austerity, fines for countries that violate them, possible suspensions of payments for one of them and the extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been for a long time, so there is no room for excuses now.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were boosting deficits, the German government invented a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany thought it should do (tax austerity plans and stability of public finances) and what its European partners, including France, were doing.
The second blow to the Central European country was when Merkel barely extended the decision to bail out Greece.
From that moment it was the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public and published opinion was against the bailout of Greece.
Finally, towards the end of October, Merkel again expressed a clear position, calling for the reform of the Union's treaties to make it possible to rescue a country and at the same time oblige private lenders to bear part of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, because it has precipitated the Irish crisis and the rest.
But his proposal, albeit a little watered down, was approved and in the months to come we should see the reform of the Union which will make these measures possible from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line that they don't think they'll cross.
And it tells us all that, even if now we have to take measures with which we may not agree too much, from that date the old way of working of the euro would have ended.
2013 will mark the birth of a new currency area, where countries that break the rules will be severely punished, may be forced to default, and in that case the private sector will also bear part of the costs.
Germany is signalling that we need to follow a tough growth path with high saving and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
An alternative based on debt and construction, with huge gaps in the balance of payments, like the one that presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, will simply not be tolerated.
The stakes are clear.
And it would be wrong not to hear it.
It is not just about bringing the government deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What we're being asked to do is much harder.
And what he absolutely must not do in these circumstances is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will bring us a greater peace.
And we'll know how to seize the opportunity that's been given to us, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has heard it too in this form and his double declaration (the reforms promised after last Saturday's meeting with big business and yesterday's announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite Merkel's criticism, the way has been opened to the thesis that we must put order in the house.
But the red line Germany has drawn is there, and they don't seem to be moving it.
And among the possibilities we are considering, we cannot exclude the possibility of abandoning a monetary zone that is too crowded with countries that are not serious.
And in that case, Germany can always tell us that she warned us.
Sport and the Law
The tricks similar to those of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax show ingenuity but not the will to escape sanction.
The alleged expulsion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) during the November 23 Champions League match against Ajax has sparked much speculation about the unsportsmanlike nature of such behaviour and whether the two players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As we know, a few minutes before the end of the match (which their team was already winning clearly), the two players deliberately lost time when they made fouls to determine the referee to show them the second yellow card.
Thus, and since Real Madrid will end up leading their group, the two players will complete the regulatory penalty during the next match of the barrage match against Auxerre and will be able to pass without cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee sanctioned the team's coach, José Mourinho, with two matches and different economic sums to the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, if not rather common in the world of football.
It's so widespread that it's part of the ethos, the unwritten but followed rules of the sport.
Part of the debate that has arisen in the case is due to the fact that this has had a team from the Real Madrid entity as protagonists (which in its anthem displays nobility and honor and which in past occasions has fined its players for similar acts) and the orchestrated dramatization, it seems, by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to his extended story of histrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate is whether this type of behaviour not expressly prohibited by the rules contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions are committed in violation of the law; in fact, they are actions that respect the sporting regulations, but seem to evade their meaning.
The question is to examine the kind of damage they cause to the sportsman's mind.
One of the assets that comprise the spirit of sport is the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that with these actions has not been endangered, that is, there has been no violent play.
Another of these goods that is referred to with fair play is to prevent the offending team from taking unfair advantage of the opposing team, which is not the case either.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of the Real Madrid players is that it does not conform to what is normally characterized as cheating or fraud of the law, because its violation of the rules was not carried out in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but their action precisely tried to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalty of the referee.
They waited and they gladly accepted the sanction.
Another issue is the type of advantage that offenders derive from the intentional wrongs examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that one does not put one's opponent at a disadvantage and one does not gain an advantage in the same match either, because obviously the result of the action presupposes leaving their own team with fewer players.
And it's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club couldn't rely on those players.
The advantage, of course, is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is an advantage in the long run, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, because the team could be eliminated suddenly and besides, with this action the players complete a penalty match and move to the second round of cards, in which the suspension due to the accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first round.
So, climbing the ladder, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
In the end, these actions are not contrary to the spirit of the sport, which still includes the making of strategic decisions that promote the maximum benefit of what the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not take action to avoid the application of the sanction (this would indeed be a clear case of fraud), but rather chose the moment in which they submitted to it.
They made a strategic decision without evading the penalty or running away from it.
Although the line between genius and law-breaking is blurred, on this occasion I think we had a clear case of genius.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises from two factors: because there were two self-expulsions and because of the way in which the director was transmitted to provoke them.
The damage to the principles of sport caused by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
