Pakistan's nuclear programme is a major concern in the United States
Islamabad is producing atomic weapons "at a rate faster than any other country".
Wikileaks leaks confirm the connection between the Taliban and Pakistan.
The content of the correspondence between the US embassy in Pakistan and the US State Department leaked by the Wikileaks portal confirms the enormous concerns that Washington is causing about Pakistan's nuclear program.
Apart from the illuminating and tasty details on the content of the conversations and thoughts of the US diplomatic representatives accredited in Islamabad, the documents reveal the fact that cooperation between the two countries in the field of nuclear security, instead of increasing, is "decreasing" and that the unstable Asian country is producing nuclear weapons "at a faster rate than any other country in the world".
The specificity of Pakistan's nuclear program - the fact that the weapons are not assembled but are stored in components to make it difficult to destroy them in the event of an attack - is a major concern in Washington.
In a report before the visit of former National Security Adviser James Jones, Ambassador Anne W. Patterson of Pakistan stated: "The proximity of some nuclear facilities to the territory under attack by the Taliban, the dispersal of nuclear materials with a high noise level and the vulnerability of the transport of nuclear materials".
