On 20th the international police force headquartered in Lyon, France, issued the order at the request of Sweden, but did not make it public until yesterday, after receiving permission from the authorities of that country.
Thus, the 188 countries of Interpol were instructed to identify or locate Assange "in order to obtain his provisional arrest and extradition".
Although Interpol cannot issue an arrest warrant for an individual affected by a red alert, many of the member countries, the organization explains, consider the red notice call a free path for arrest -- which the national police force must carry out -- especially if they have a bilateral extradition agreement, as is the case with Sweden and England, where Assange is believed to be.
The move outraged Assange's lawyers, who yesterday published a letter denouncing the fact that the 39-year-old Wikileaks founder had shown himself willing to answer questions from Swedish authorities via video conference.
