With literature, we put our finger on the wound.
The second stage of the Pleasures of Language was a walk in which the participants showcased their storytelling skills.
"Sex in the language, I understand, but... finger on the wound? What do they expect from me?", asked the writer Luisa Valenzuela, invited to open the second stage of the Pleasures of the language, a cycle that celebrates literature in Spanish and which this time used the subtitle of her question (during another fair the round table was dedicated to Sex in the language, she explained).
The finger on the wound"...it puts us in a state of embarrassment", the Argentine writer gently launched to the audience, most of whom were young, who had gathered at the International Book Fair of Guadalajara (FIL) to listen to this table moderated by Marisol Shultz and in which Valenzuela, Sergio Ramírez, Mayra Montero and Luis García Montero participated.
Luisa Valenzuela read a text dedicated to Gonzalo Celorio that Shultz later defined as a great story, with Luisa in the first person as the protagonist who seeks to know what the "wound" is, she goes from one doctor to another, without getting an answer, only clues in the same narrative thread.
She left the infectious disease clinic with the conviction that "patience is not my strong suit, it may be my wound".
Finally, after a frustrated approach with the trauma specialist who took his breath away in the middle of the corridor, but who explained that wound is not a scientific term; it is the psychoanalyst who reveals the mystery: "the wound is what is actually open, the symbolic is the scar".
The protagonist sighs with relief and concludes: "on the wound I could only know that it is that which is opened in reality and that it does not exist", but convinced of the fact that the pleasures and the traps of the language must be very closely linked.
Valenzuela, the writer, played both.
The Nicaraguan Sergio Ramírez also presented a delightful narrative titled "Elohim to the Invention", where the finger on the wound is not named but at a certain moment is discovered.
With touches of magical realism, he tells of a famous sorceress who touched clouds, brought back people who had gone far or repaired virtues that a young lady had lost, a narrative that turns to talk then America, the great news that had its own chroniclers from the beginning and quotes Bernal Díaz del Castillo who criticizes the excesses of the narratives of the conquering captains.
"Cervantes, who invented us all, "laughed at the false witnesses who appeared in the stories presented as real, "but in a way that would never have told the history of America "with an imagination that lacked even modesty".
Nevertheless, he pointed out, "fools and liars have the best imagination" and here reality converges with lies, it is no longer known which part of the narrative belongs to one band or the other, where fiction literature reaches its peak.
This is called the 'Cervantes tradition'.
"It is by inheritance that one is what one is told".
In turn, the writer Mayra Montyero noted and applauded the variety of interpretations provoked by the invitation of the FIL with her round table Le doit sur la plaie.
The Cuban-Puerto Rican woman spoke about the great scourge of social violence that her country is going through - and Latin America is going through - produced by the drug trafficking and drug sales disputes.
"I think that good literature, good poetry and good songs contain an unspoken commitment which is of course not premeditated", she said, after mentioning that the reality of literature is the communication and the dimension of the commitment that is established between the author and the readers, and that this is a "chemical reaction" of the latter.
The evening ended with the intervention of the Spanish poet Luis García Montero who also underlined "it must be on the writer's wound committed".
He considered that in a world which lives at great speed also in terms of intellectual habits and the control of consciences which turns to the advantage of dogmatism, "behind every affirmation there is a little no and behind every negation there is a little yes".
"To be masters of our own feelings and masters of reality, we must nuance: and nuance means many times to put the finger on the wound and disturb people who feel very comfortable thinking in caricature, in black and white, in established ideas and without nuance and also disturb the powers that prefer a world in black and white", he said, inviting to recover the sense of writing.
