The European Union is changing the rules for obtaining a visa
Individuals must go to the Visa Applicant Service Centres before their interview in the Consular Section; the cost and waiting time will be reduced.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa processing procedure at the US Embassy and Consulates will change.
Under the new procedure, most applicants will have to present themselves at the Visa Applicant Service Centres (VASCs) before their interview in the Consular Section.
The applicant's biometric information will be collected by ASC staff and reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, among which are the following:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, there will be no need to make one payment to get an appointment, another payment for processing the visa and another for the courier to deliver the document.
The applicant will make a single payment covering all three services.
The current rate will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (this includes visas for temporary workers) and $390 for visas for traders and investors.
Persons wishing to renew their visa will not be required to attend an interview with the Consular Representative, but will only be required to attend the nearest CSA where they will present documents and have their fingerprints taken.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be taken in the ASC, applicants who wish to have a second interview in the Consular Section will be there for a shorter period than before.
Similarly, visa applicants at the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer have to pay the additional $26 service fee.
For more information on the new procedure for applying for a visa, please visit the following page: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/bulletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
NASA will announce the discovery of extraterrestrial life
The U.S. space agency has cited the press to announce tomorrow a discovery that will have an impact on the search for life in space.
The National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) of the United States will announce tomorrow, Thursday, an astrobiological discovery that could prove the theory of the existence of extraterrestrial life.
The discovery will be presented at a press conference tomorrow Thursday at 1:00 p.m. at NASA headquarters in Washington for experts in astrobiology, the science that studies the origin, evolution, distribution and future of life in the universe.
When quoted by the press, NASA assured that it would present "any impact on the search for extraterrestrial life", which has sparked speculation from experts in other countries.
The discovery could prove the theory that there are creatures like us in hostile environments that were thought to be uninhabited and would put on the table the possibility of becoming human-like intelligent beings if their living conditions are improved.
It seems that a microbe discovered at the bottom of Mono Lake in Yosemite National Park, California, lives in an environment that was thought to be too poisonous for any life form because the lake is rich in arsenic.
In any case, the creature uses arsenic as a way of life, and this ability leads us to believe that similar life might exist on other planets that don't have our beneficial atmosphere.
If these organisms use arsenic in their metabolism, say astrobiologists, it proves that "there is another form of life, a second form of life, different from the one we know".
The space agency will announce the full extent of the findings at a press conference tomorrow, Thursday.
The conference will be attended by geobiologist Pamela Conrad, who studies the possibility of life on Mars; and biologist Steven Benner, one of the scientists studying Titan (the largest satellite of Saturn), in the perspective that its chemistry is similar to that of the Earth.
