A global plan to improve lighting
The UN yesterday proposed in Cancún a plan to upgrade domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to achieve a reduction in greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions of almost one third of the additional reduction needed to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is in line with the major concrete projects that the UN hopes to see adopted in Cancún to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments by the industrialized countries.
According to the plan tabled yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs which still control 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by compact fluorescent bulbs or, better, by light emitting diode (LED) bulbs, the bulk of the 1.8 billion tons of GHG emitted on the planet to illuminate humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
That's the equivalent of 70% of the emissions from the world's car fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, the major emitters, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that are expected to bring global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But we'll have to subtract another 5 Gt from this balance to get to a level of 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 to avoid it going out of control.
In incandescent light bulbs, 95 percent of the energy is dissipated as heat and the remaining 5 percent as light.
With compact fluorescent bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, this energy demand is reduced by two times.
Compact bulbs last on average from 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched this week by the manufacturer Philips - which was also involved in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, which gives an idea of the savings that could be made with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit very little heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about the use of fluocompact bulbs because they contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers put in place safety precautions.
But, says the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluorescent bulb, but rather coal-fired power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce electricity wasted in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury a year.
The report details the gains that each country would make from this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save $1 billion a year in electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants that would cost $2.5 billion to build.
