Hackers and spies on the run
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it is an apparent scandal, a scandal which appears as such only in the face of the hypocrisy which governs relations between States, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes at the international level and foreshadows a future dominated by regression.
But let's go in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by a secret service (of any nation) is composed exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only report what for months ago could be read in any newspaper (except those owned by Berlusconi), and the sinister caricatural profile of Khadafi has long been for sketch cabaret artists.
The rule that secret files should only be composed of news that is already known is essential to the dynamics of secret services, and not just in this century.
If you go to a bookstore devoted to esoteric publications, you will find that each book (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rose-Croix) repeats exactly what was already written in the previous books.
This is not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do unpublished research (nor does he know where to look for information about the nonexistent), but because those who devote themselves to the occult believe only in what they already know, and this confirms what they have already learned.
That's the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
Same goes for the classified files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited in mind) is the head of the secret services (otherwise he could be, I don't know, editor of Libération), who only holds as true what he recognizes.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the US embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same as the one Newsweek had published the week before.
Then why did the disclosures on these files make such a fuss ?
On the one hand, they say what every educated person already knows, namely that embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War, and since heads of state can call each other or fly to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, except for a few small representative exercises, have become centers of espionage.
Any spectator of investigative films knows this very well, and it is only out of hypocrisy that we pretend to ignore it.
However, the act of repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to cast American diplomacy in a bad light.
Second, the idea that any hacker could capture the most secret secrets of the world's most powerful country is a significant blow to the State Department's prestige.
The scandal therefore does not put the victims in crisis so much as the "executioners".
But let's get to the deep nature of what happened.
Back in Orwell's time, you could think of any power as a Big Brother who controlled every move of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had been completely fulfilled since, being able to control every move through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway taken and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as is happening now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker -- elected as the citizen's avenger -- can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets hold on?
It is true, as Georg Simmel has said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that anything we know about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed a secret void of secrets, because it is in the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means to take away all power from her.
WikiLeaks did no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but it did too much harm to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound inflicted on a very powerful power ?
It is clear that in the future, states will no longer be able to put any information online - it would be like putting it on a billboard on a street corner.
But it is equally clear that with today's technology, it is futile to hope to maintain confidential reports over the telephone.
Nothing like finding out if and when a head of state flew in and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved relations be maintained in the future?
I know that my prediction is science fiction at this point, and therefore a novel, but I am forced to imagine government agents traveling discreetly in stagecoaches on uncontrolled routes, carrying only memorized messages or, at most, hiding the rare information written on the heel of a shoe.
The information will be kept in a single copy in locked drawers: after all, the Watergate spy attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I have had the opportunity to write that technology is now advancing in a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has brought back wired telegraph.
Whereas the analogue videocassette had allowed film researchers to explore a film step by step, going back and forth and discovering all the secrets of editing, the digital CD now only allows one to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. by macro-portion.
High-speed trains take from Rome to Milan three hours, while air travel, including travel by train, takes three and a half hours.
It is not surprising, then, that politics and communications technology have returned to horse-drawn carriages.
One last thing to note.
In the past, the press tried to understand what was going on in the secret embassies.
Now it's the embassies that are asking the press for confidential information.
Climate: how France is rigging its funding promises
One year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to examine the fulfilment of the promises of rapidly unlocked financing (so-called fast start or early financing) made by the developed countries.
And the big French gadgets are revealed.
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries committed to providing 30 billion dollars between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged 7.2 billion euros over three years and France 1.26 billion euros (or 420 million per year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU played a big game to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start funding: report detailing the action of its Member States, press conference, grand side event, distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation is appreciated and appreciated for what it is: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of accuracy.
The EU announces that it has released €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to meet its €7.2 billion commitment in 2012.
But when you look at the details, things are more complicated.
This money must be, according to the Copenhagen agreement, 'new and additional' in order to ensure that additional effort is made without detriment to ODA.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits him best.
The European Commission, for example, took 2009 as a reference year: international financing is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years in the form of fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks in terms of year or in terms of level of official development assistance.
By contrast, France considers that the financing of 'all new projects' in 2010 is 'new and additional'.
In other words, there is no reference to expenditure in previous years or to the overall level of ODA.
In practical terms, the total amount of French aid to the developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), and France claims to be fulfilling its commitment to provide 'new and additional' financing.
Another crucial element is the distribution of donations and loans.
Again, there are no rules and each person chooses his own calculation method.
Some countries, such as France, consider that 1 € lent is equal to 1 € given.
Of course, this is hardly justifiable.
While the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often emission-mitigation projects based on more efficient technologies), it is fallacious to present a euro that is to be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given away... At most, only the cost of the loan to the lending country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate) should be counted as part of its commitments.
But France has no use for such reasoning: it "meets" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% donations (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union which uses the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46% of this, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia (among others) meet their commitments with 100% of the donations.
In other words, while the vast majority of the European Union puts in 1 euro to meet its commitment, France puts in only 10 cents and considers the effort comparable.
What a trick!
In short, in its financing of the fast start, France is committing a double fraud: on the one hand, on the evolution of the action over time and, on the other hand, on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only EUR 36.1 million, it is able to make it appear that it is spending EUR 420 million "new and additional" in line with its promises.
The manipulation of the Treasury (as it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other member states continue to give if they just lend?) and in the negotiations since the developing countries are not completely fooled...
The early financing chapter is a small, relatively short-term issue in the climate discussion as a whole.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the huge machine that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that's not the case.
In any case, it is essential to learn the lessons of this first year of early financing.
First, France could announce a change in its accounting system for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could advance discussions on the issues of long-term financing (another crucial topic currently under discussion): the question of 'additionality' or the accounting of loans cannot be avoided.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
The hope is therefore in the new Minister of the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement on France's fast start and its vision of 'additionality' and the use of loans would increase the level of international confidence needed to move the discussions forward.
